<FIRST>r a AM-StormKaren 1stLd-Writethru a0716 12-02 0241</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Storm Karen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0716,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weather Service Lifts Tropical Storm Warnings for Cuba</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS penultimate graf to UPDATE with later position.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tropical Storm Karen moved southwest away from Cuba
on Friday after dumping heavy rain on the island.
   Tropical storm warnings for Cuba were lifted by the National
Hurricane Center in Coral Gables, Fla.
   The storm, moving in a clockwise loop, could make a complete
circle in the Caribbean if it stays together long enough to meet
with a big funnel trough located in the Gulf of Mexico, forecaster
Bob Case said.
   ``That could cause the storm to move to the northeast in a big
circle,'' Case said.
   But, there is a 50-50 chance the storm will dissipate before
then, he said.
   ``We don't see any major dramatic effect on land areas,'' he
said.
   The system surprised forecasters by achieving tropical storm
strength Thursday when its winds hit 39 mph.
   Rainfall reports Thursday from Cuba included more than 14 inches
at Punta del Este on the Isle of Youth, more than seven inches in
Matanzas and nearly five inches in Havana.
   At 10:30 p.m. EST Friday, the center of the storm was located
near latitude 17.8 north, longitude 85.2 west, or about 175 miles
east of Belize. Karen's highest sustained winds were near 40 mph.
   The hurricane season begins June 1 and ends Nov. 30. However,
hurricanes have been recorded in every month but April.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
