<FIRST>r a AM-AbductedNun     12-02 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Abducted Nun,0213</SECOND>
<UNK>Senator Urges Investigation Into Abduction of Nun in Guatemala</UNK>
<DATELINE>ALBUQUERQUE, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Sen. Jeff Bingaman called on
Secretary of State James Baker on Friday to order an investigation
into the abduction and torture of a New Mexico nun in Guatemala
last month.
   Sister Diana Ortiz of Grants, N.M., was abducted Nov. 2 from a
retreat house in Antigua, about 30 miles from Guatemala City, and
released a day later. In his letter to Baker dated Friday,
Bingaman, D-N.M., said Ms. Ortiz was ``subjected to a 24-hour
interrogation that included both physical and sexual abuse.''
   ``There are indications that a man with a North American accent
who finally stepped in to stop the physical abuse may have been
associated with the U.S. Embassy,'' Bingaman's letter said.
   This possibility ``warrants an expeditious but thorough
investigation,'' the letter said, without giving further details.
   A State Department duty officer said nobody would be available
for comment until Saturday.
   In his letter, the senator also enclosed press reports
indicating a man wearing a Guatemalan police uniform participated
in the abduction.
   Sister Ortiz had been a school teacher in rural Huehuetenango
Province prior to her abduction. Her order, the Ursuline Sisters,
has indicated she will not return to Guatemala.
</TEXT>
