<FIRST>r a PM-VoterRegistration     12-02 0213</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voter Registration,0219</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iowa Puts Voter Registration Forms in Phone Books</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iowa is distributing voter registration
forms inside each copy of the new telephone book, and officials
hope the process catches on in other states.
   ``In every election, fewer and fewer people vote in America,''
Secretary of State Elaine Baxter said Friday. ``We're making Iowa
the leader in convenient voter registration procedures.''
   Telephone books currently being distributed by US West, the
Denver-based regional phone company, include voter registration
forms at the bottom of one of the instruction pages. The form can
be clipped and mailed in an envelope to the county auditor.
   State income tax booklets that will be sent out at the end of
the year also will include voter registration forms, under
legislation enacted this year.
   Earl Mix, a US West vice president, said Iowa is the first state
in which the forms will be included in telephone books. He
predicted other states would follow suit.
   ``I hope that this becomes a model for the voter registration
process,'' he said.
   US West distributes nearly 2.2 million telephone books in Iowa,
Mix said. There are more than 1.5 million registered voters in
Iowa, and an estimated 500,000 eligible voters who are not
registered, Ms. Baxter said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
