<FIRST>r a AM-Fusion-Pons     12-02 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fusion-Pons,0483</SECOND>
<HEAD>Utah Officials Say Japanese Fusion Work Spawning Patent Concerns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japanese researchers have duplicated
recent U.S. ``cold'' fusion experiments and are reaching for the
lead in the emerging technology, one of the scientists who touched
off the furor complained Friday.
   A U.S. Department of Energy panel recently refused to back a
national nuclear fusion program based on discoveries by University
of Utah electrochemist B. Stanley Pons and a British colleague,
Martin Fleischmann.
   Physicists contend the Utah research has been largely
discredited because other experimenters have failed to fully
duplicate Pons' and Fleischmann's results.
   But Pons said Friday that Japan and India are making major
investments in nuclear fusion research and development that could
wrest leadership in the field away from the U.S.
   In March, Pons and Fleischmann said they had achieved room
temperature, or ``cold'' fusion, by immersing in deuterium-rich
heavy water rods of palladium inside electrically charged platinum
coils. The two said the reaction yield heat equivalent to 100 times
the energy needed to produce the reaction.
   ``They've been duplicating our experiments since late March,''
Pons said. ``The Japanese and Indians are doing just what's
obvious. They're doing the research needed to find out if it's
feasible or not, and they're finding it is.''
   A bitter Pons said if the U.S. does lose its lead in nuclear
fusion research, the blame should rest squarely on the shoulders of
the DOE's Energy Research Advisory Board. The board recently
concluded there is no conclusive evidence that Pons and Fleischmann
actually produced fusion.
   ``We've tried to tell the country that research money is the
only way to cover these (developments) properly, and its pretty
obvious that's not going to get done,'' Pons said. ``We certainly
can't match the scope of the work that the Japanese ... are doing.''
   Japanese physicists at Japan's Nagoya University said in the
November issue of the English-language Japanese Journal of Applied
Physics that fusion had occurred spontaneously between two
palladium electrodes in a flask filled with deuterium gas.
   The Japanese said the major difference between their work and
that of Pons and Fleischmann was the use of deuterium gas instead
of heavy water.
   However, Pons he and Fleischmann already have carried out the
same experiment as the Japanese, and have applied for a patent on
the procedure.
   Japanese researchers point out their own experiments yielded a
high level of neutron emissions _ up to 20,000 times the normal
background level. That is one possible indicator of a fusion
reaction.
   Topping that, another group of researchers at Osaka University
this week reported detecting neutron levels 2.5 million times
normal levels in a cold-fusion experiment using platinum electrodes
in heavy water.
   In addition to the Japanese and India, fusion research also
reportedly is under way in China and the Soviet Union.
</TEXT>
