<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0111EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SalvadorProtest     12-02 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador Protest,0302</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daniel Berrigan, 22 Others Arrested in Salvador Protest</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHEVEL JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. marshals arrested 23 people, including
activist Jesuit priest Daniel Berrigan, who blocked elevators in a
federal building Friday to protest government support for El
Salvador.
   The arrests followed a confrontation between U.S. Attorney John
Volz and the Rev. Gerald Fagin, head of the Southern Province of
Jesuits. Fagin was not arrested but said he supported the protest.
   ``I'm a Catholic and I'm sympathetic to your cause, but I can't
allow you to break the law,'' Volz told the demonstrators just
before ordering their arrest.
   ``We are upholding our civil disobedience rights,'' said Fagin.
   Prior to being arrested, Berrigan defended the protest to
reporters.
   ``This is a protest salvaging our own humanity,'' he said.
   The protests coincided with the second day of a two-day memorial
held by Jesuit-run Loyola University for six Jesuit priests
murdered recently in El Salvador.
   There was no violence by the 80 or so protesters. Fifteen men
and eight women were handcuffed and arrested later, then were
arraigned on misdemeanor obstruction charges and released without
having to post bail.
   The demonstration at the 13-story building's eight elevators
began about 12:45 p.m., capping a day of prayer, song and protest
joined by numerous Jesuit leaders, nuns and local high school and
college students.
   Among them were students from Loyola University, where Berrigan,
who began his social activism with his brother during the 1960s, is
teaching sociology this semester.
   Protesters blocked access to elevators by sitting in the
doorways, preventing doors from closing. Power to the elevators
appeared to have been shut off shortly after the protest began and
workers in the building headed for the stairs.
</TEXT>
