<DOCNO> AP891202-0012 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0310EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Salvador-American     12-02 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador-American,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Salvadoran Officials Have Softer Words for Arrested American</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Salvadoran officials are questioning
whether an American woman who was arrested in San Salvador after
weapons and explosives were found in the back yard of the home she
rented was willfully helping rebels.
   Ricardo Valdivieso, the Salvadoran undersecretary of foreign
affairs, suggested Friday at a news conference that Jennifer J.
Casolo may be ``a naive person who has been used by'' the leftist
rebels and that ``unfortunately she was found in the house at the
time.''
   Col. Carlos Amando Aviles, a spokesman for the Salvadoran
military, told the same news conference at the National Press Club
that he knows Casolo and ``she is a very nice, honest person that I
consider a good American.''
   Sen. Christopher Dodd, D-Conn., chairman of the Western
Hemisphere subcommittee of the Foreign Relations Committee, said he
was heartened by the statements about Casolo, a Connecticut native.
   ``I am encouraged by these statements, and I hope they reflect a
change in attitude by the Salvadoran authorities that will result
in the swift and favorable resolution of the case against Jennifer
Casolo,'' Dodd said.
   Still, Salvadoran President Alfredo Cristiani indicated in San
Salvador that ``a judicial process'' was called for.
   ``We feel that anybody that breaks the laws in this country, no
matter what nationality they are, should be submitted to the
judicial process,'' Cristiani said at a news conference.
   ``If there is enough proof, and apparently in this case there
is, in order to start a judicial process, one will be started,'' he
said.
   Of former Attorney General Ramsey Clark, who was in El Salvador
to advise Casolo, Cristiani said: ``If he is involved in any way in
the politics of El Salvador then his permit (visa) will be revoked
immediately.''
   Casolo, 28, has maintained she is innocent of any military
connection with the rebels. She works in El Salvador as a
representative of the San Antonio, Texas-based Christian Education
Seminars, providing tours for Americans who come to see and study
the country.
   She was arrested a week ago after Salvadoran officials, acting
on a tip from a captured rebel, dug up the back yard of the house
she had been renting for the past three months and found dynamite
and thousands of rounds of rifle ammunition.
   Friends suggested she was framed by the Salvadoran government,
but the Bush administration took a different view.
   White House press secretary Marlin Fitzwater said Monday, ``This
is hardly a case of a someone having a few things flipped in their
shopping bag on the way home.'' And the Justice Department began
reviewing the case to determine if she broke the U.S. Neutrality
Act.
   Fitzwater took a softer approach Wednesday, saying U.S.
officials were ``monitoring her case closely to assure she is well
treated.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
