<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0312EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-DefenseSecretaries     12-02 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Defense Secretaries,0473</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Defense Secretaries Still Skeptical of Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHIL WEST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Despite the rapid political change in
Eastern Europe and the role Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev is
playing there, six former U.S. defense secretaries are still
skeptical of the permanence of the shift.
   ``I think that we should recognize that although Mr. Gorbachev
is immensely popular in Western Europe and even in the United
States that his popularity, his position in the Soviet Union itself
has weakened dramatically,'' said James Schlesinger, who served
from 1973 to 1975 in the Nixon and Ford administrations.
   Schlesinger said Friday at the Third Annual Report of the
Secretaries of Defense that Gorbachev is walking a fine line that
could tumble him from power if his reforms become too politically
and financially costly.
   ``The Soviet economy is in serious decline. There is a
possibility of a recession within the Soviet Union, and Mr.
Gorbachev's position is precarious. He may or may not survive, and
it probably is in our interest that he survive.''
   The others participating in the forum, Caspar Weinberger, Melvin
Laird, Robert McNamara, Frank Carlucci and Donald Rumsfeld, agreed
that the Soviet reform spirit might not last. The panel discussion
was sponsored by the nonprofit Southern Center for International
Studies in Atlanta.
   Gorbachev and President Bush were in Malta to hold a weekend
summit aboard U.S. and Soviet warships. Bush praised Gorbachev
Friday as ``a dynamic new Soviet leader'' whose policies of
openness and other reforms are advancing the cause of world peace.
   But Weinberger, who served as Ronald Reagan's defense secretary
from 1981 to 1987, warned, ``The Cold War is not over.''
   Weinberger said the Soviet Union can transform soldiers into
farmers _ and back again _ in a matter of days. They can just as
easily change their party leaders, Weinberger said.
   He cited the reversal of what appeared to be democratic reforms
in China when the army cleared Tiananmen Square of demonstrators.
   ``The Soviet Union is quite capable of reversing these things,
like firing into crowds,'' Weinberger said.
   Still, the former defense secretaries agreed that the opening of
the Berlin Wall and relaxed travel in Warsaw Pact nations could
lead to U.S. troop reductions in Europe. And each said the United
States should keep hands off any attempts at reunifying Germany.
   ``We'll be bringing Americans home. And you'll be seeing that by
the end of the year,'' predicted Laird, Richard Nixon's defense
secretary from 1969 to 1973.
   Schlesinger said the changes sweeping Europe are staggering.
   ``The Warsaw Pact threat is quite different. For that reason, we
can spend somewhat less than we have on our readiness posture in
Western Europe. And I stress somewhat less,'' Schlesinger said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
