<FIRST>r a PM-Virus-Monkey     12-02 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Virus-Monkey,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deadly Virus Found in Three Monkeys</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FREDERICK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scientists who began examining the
carcasses of 100 laboratory monkeys imported from the Philippines
by a Virginia firm say they have so far discovered three with the
ebola virus, considered the deadliest virus to humans before AIDS
was discovered.
   Health officials also say they are monitoring the 25 employees
at the Virginia research firm that had received the monkeys in
October even though they believe the disease would have turned up
in the employees by now if any had been infected. Officials said
none of the employees have shown any symptoms.
   The monkeys had been shipped to Hazleton Research Products of
Reston, Va., a subsidiary of Corning Glass Corp. that uses primates
for cosmetics and drug testing.
   This is the first time the virus has been found in a non-human
and the first time it had been found in the United States. The
discovery of the first infected monkey was announced earlier this
week.
   ``We don't know where they got the virus,'' Charles Dasey, a
spokesman at the Army Medical Research Institute of Infectious
Diseases at Fort Detrick in Frederick, Md., said Friday.
   ``We're continuing to help Hazleton and public health officials
determine how far it has spread through the monkey colony,'' he
said.
   In mid-November, medical investigators helped Hazleton determine
that some of the monkeys suffered from simian hemorrhagic fever and
that one monkey had the ebola virus. All of the animals in the
shipment were then destroyed, authorities said.
   Since then, 17 monkey carcasses have been sent to Fort Detrick
for necropsies, similar to autopsies in humans. The first seven
arrived Wednesday, and three, including the initial animal, had the
virus.
   Ten more delivered Friday have not been examined, Dasey said. It
was not immediately known when the remaining necropsies would be
performed.
   The ebola virus causes a contagious disease that is transmitted
through body fluids and secretions, though not through casual
contact, according to Dr. Susan Fishel-Hoch of the institute.
   It was first identified in Zaire in 1976, where over 500 people
died.
   The virus kills 50 percent to 90 percent of those it infects.
There is no vaccine.
   Health officials said Friday that Hazleton employees who had
worked with the monkeys had worn surgical masks, gowns and gloves
on the job.
   ``At this point, I don't see where we have a health problem,''
said Barbara Mitchell, spokeswoman for the Virginia Department of
Health in Richmond. ``We probably would have seen something by now
if someone was infected, but we're still taking every precaution we
can.''
   Mitchell said the 25 workers will be examined daily for the next
three weeks in cooperation with the Centers for Disease Control in
Atlanta.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
