<FIRST>r w PM-Osprey     12-02 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Osprey,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pentagon Shuts Off Money For Osprey Aircraft</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Defense Department has ordered an
immediate halt to all production spending on the V-22 Osprey, the
vertical takeoff plane the Marines and members of Congress want but
the administration wants to cancel.
   Deputy Defense Secretary Donald J. Atwood sent instructions
Friday to Navy Secretary H. Lawrence Garrett III to ``terminate
forthwith'' all contracts financed out of the previous fiscal
year's $334 million for procurement, said Lt. Cmdr. Gregg Hartung,
a department spokesman.
   Those contracts were for items that take a long time to supply,
the so-called ``long lead'' items.
   Though all $334 million had been obligated, ``much of it remains
unspent,'' said Hartung, reading from Atwood's memo.
   Congress this fiscal year refused the administration's request
to kill the plane, but did limit its appropriation of $255 million
to research and development.
   Though the Marines had placed a high priority on the Osprey to
ferry troops ashore from ships off landing beaches, Defense
Secretary Dick Cheney decided that the $27 billion needed for the
desired fleet of aircraft could be better spent elsewhere and
helicopters used for the ferry job.
   Backers of the plane, to built near Fort Worth, Texas, by a
joint endeavor of Boeing Corp. and Bell Helicopter Textron, argued
that it could be enormously useful in easing airspace congestion
around heavily used airports, but critics retorted that if it were
commercially valuable, airlines and manufacturers would finance it
themselves.
</TEXT>
