<FIRST>r a PM-RockyFlats     12-02 0589</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rocky Flats,0608</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rocky Flats Halts Plutonium Production Indefinitely</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal government halted operations at
the Rocky Flats nuclear weapons plant to resolve safety questions
including whether enough plutonium dust has accumulated in the
pipes to cause an uncontrolled nuclear reaction.
   Energy Secretary James Watkins announced a major management
shakeup at the plant and said it would not reopen until the
government and the plant's new contractor _ EG&amp;G Inc. _ are
satisfied safety concerns have been met.
   At a news conference at the plant, 16 miles north of Denver,
Watkins said plutonium operations had been scaled back 20 percent
and would be shut down altogether in the coming days.
   Watkins acknowledged that any long-term shutdown could seriously
affect the United States' nuclear weapons capability. The plant is
the only one of its kind in the United States that makes plutonium
triggers for nuclear weapons. Other plants in the nuclear weapons
industry that have been at least partly shut down in the last two
years include the Savannah River Site in South Carolina, the
plutonium processing plant at the Hanford Reservation in
Washington, and the Feed Materials Production Center, a uranium
plant in Ohio.
   Rocky Flats has been plagued by safety accusations in recent
years and is the target of a federal criminal probe that so far has
not resulted in indictments. Earlier this fall, DOE terminated its
management agreement with Rockwell International Corp. and signed a
new accord with EG&amp;G, which is scheduled to take over fully Jan. 1.
   After touring the plant, Watkins said, ``Although no major
hardware problems were identified by the Department of Energy team,
conduct of operations, standards of performance, engineering
support and management structure remain deficient.''
   Among the safety concerns he cited was an October report issued
by a team of independent investigators which found weapon-grade
plutonium in a pipe that serves as an exhaust ventilation duct at
one of the plant's main buildings.
   Initial reports indicated there was enough plutonium present _
about 12 pounds _ to cause ``criticality,'' or a nuclear reaction,
but another study found there was less plutonium in the ducts than
originally thought. Both reports said there was no evidence a
reaction had occurred.
   Watkins said the criticality issue does not pose a public safety
threat.
   ``Nevertheless, because it is an important safety issue, I am
asking EG&amp;G to independently review the report's findings and
produce their own action plan,'' he said.
   Gov. Roy Romer, who was present at Watkins' news conference,
said the decision to shut down plutonium processing at Rocky Flats
shows a new commitment by DOE to safety. He added:
   ``It's obvious that the proof is in the pudding, and it's my job
as governor of Colorado to make sure the citizens are safe.''
   Rep. David Skaggs, D-Colo., who earlier called for a complete
shutdown at Rocky Flats, said Watkins ``seems to be taking a
positive, if somewhat uncertain step, but in the right direction.''
   Skaggs said it was unclear how the shutdown period at Rocky
Flats would be evaluated and verified.
   Watkins admitted that DOE made major mistakes at Rocky Flats.
   ``We did not bring our management into the modern world and
we're going to do that now,'' he said.
   Part of the shutdown period will be dedicated to safety
training, Watkins said. He said it would be necessary to regain
public trust.
   ``Of course we have a credibility problem. What we are trying to
do now is regain it,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
