<FIRST>r w PM-NBC-GE     12-02 0240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NBC-GE,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Reports Network Removes Reference to Parent Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A producer at NBC's ``Today'' show says his
deletion of an unfavorable reference to General Electric Co. in a
report on defective aircraft engine bolts had nothing to do with
GE's ownership of the network.
   ``I definitely wasn't more careful because GE was involved,''
executive producer Marty Ryan told The Washington Post in a story
published today.
   The original report said that GE, a manufacturer of aircraft
engines among other things, accepted defective bolts from a
supplier and for eight years did not require that the supplier
certify the product's quality.
   The report, broadcast Thursday on the network's morning show,
mentioned other manufacturers, but only the part pertaining to GE
was cut, the newspaper said. Ryan said ``an expanded spot'' about
the GE allegations will air on the show next week.
   Ryan said he did not think the reporter, Peter Karl of WMAQ-TV
in Chicago, had ``journalistically (covered) all his bases.'' The
Chicago station had prepared and originally aired the report.
   Ryan called the omission ``one of those things.''
   Karl said he had been asked by ``Today'' show producers whether
he had contacted GE for comment on the report. The reporter said he
had done so on several occasions.
   ``My view is that you make a mistake when you treat your
employer differently than anybody else,'' Ron Magers, an anchorman
at WMAQ, was quoted as saying.
</TEXT>
