<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0215EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-India 1stLd-Writethru   12-02 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0701,0722</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leader of Opposition Coalition Named Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs with Singh sworn in, Gandhi offering congratulations;
picks up 4th pvs, `Singh's selection...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIJAY JOSHI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vishwanath Pratap Singh was sworn in as
prime minister Saturday to replace Rajiv Gandhi, and the new leader
said his first goal would be to bring dignity to India, whose
previous government was dogged by allegations of corruption.
   President Ramaswamy Venkataraman, who administered the oath of
office at the presidential palace, has given Singh 30 days to prove
his National Front coalition can muster a vote of confidence in the
new Parliament.
   Gandhi, now consigned to the role of opposition leader, smiled
as he approached Singh after the 10-minute ceremony. He was one of
the first to offer congratulations.
   On Friday, Singh also was elected parliamentary leader of the
centrist National Front and of the coalition's largest party, the
Janata Dal.
   Singh's selection came after last-minute conferences, a
fistfight, and allegations of skullduggery within the front, which
is united by little more than antipathy to Gandhi and the Congress
Party.
   It formed a cohesive opposition force to defeat Gandhi in
national elections Nov. 22-26.
   ``My first task is to restore the dignity of the country,''
Singh said Friday. ``We should make an India of which every Indian
will be proud.''
   The 58-year-old former defense minister said foreign policy
would remain largely unaltered and that the government would take
the Congress Party into confidence on ``national issues.''
   The Janata Dal has 141 of the National Front's 144 seats in
Parliament's new policy-making lower house. The other three seats
went to smaller parties in the coalition. Gandhi's party has 192
seats, and its allies have another 17.
   The National Front has also been promised support by the
Bharatiya Janata Party, which has 88 seats, and by a combination of
left-wing groups, which won 51 constituencies.
   That would give the coalition and its tacit allies 283 seats _
enough to carry a vote of confidence in the government.
   Although the Congress Party has more seats than the National
Front, it would have had more trouble forming a coalition.
   Gandhi became prime minister in 1984 after the assassination of
his mother, Prime Minister Indira Gandhi. His aides predicted the
new government will fall apart before its five-year term expires,
clearing the way for new elections and the Congress Party's return
to power. The party governed India for nearly all India's 42 years
of independence.
   The Congress Party said it would not stake a claim to form the
government. Instead, it appeared prepared to wait to see if Singh
could preserve a government with his ideologically diverse allies.
   Coalition members said Thursday that Singh, a former defense
minister, was the only candidate for prime minister. But Singh's
professed reluctance for the job spurred two other candidates,
Chandra Shekhar and Devi Lal, to enter the fray.
   A whirlwind of consultations began Friday as Singh and other
leaders drove from house to house and office to office.
   A few hours before Singh was named prime minister, riot police
quelled fistfights between supporters of Singh and Chandra Shekhar
in the street outside Chandra Shekhar's home.
   Ram Jethmalani, a senior member of the National Front, was
punched and kicked by supporters of Chandra Shekhar when he got out
of his car to begin a hunger strike aimed at persuading Chandra
Shekhar to step aside in favor of Singh.
   The 78-year-old Jethmalani, one of India's top criminal lawyers,
fell to the ground as the two sides traded punches.
   Chandra Shekhar stalked out of the parliamtentary meeting after
Singh was chosen party leader.
   Singh was in Gandhi's Cabinet until 1987, when he resigned amid
reports his investigations into government corruption were proving
embarrassing to the prime minister.
   Shortly afterward, Swedish and Indian newspaper and radio
reports disclosed the Swedish arms manufacturer AB Bofors paid as
much as $50 million in commissions and kickbacks to get a $1.4
billion contract to supply the Indian army with artillery guns.
   Gandhi vigorously denied wrongdoing, and the charges have never
been proved, but they raised serious questions about the Gandhi's
integrity and cost him popular support.
</TEXT>
