<FIRST>r a PM-Comaneci     12-02 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Comaneci,0537</SECOND>
<HEAD>Perfect Gymnast Lands in U.S.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BETH J. HARPAZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nadia Comaneci, who vaulted gracefully into
American hearts as a tiny gymnast performing airy gyrations in the
1976 Olympics, has leaped what remains of the Iron Curtain to come
live in America.
   The 28-year-old Comaneci, who defected from Romania on Tuesday,
flew here Friday on the Pan Am plane ``Liberty Bell'' from Vienna.
   ``I'm very happy because I'm here in America and I wanted from
long time to come here,'' she said in halting English at a news
conference at John F. Kennedy International Airport. ``I wanted to
have a free life.''
   Comaneci contacted a U.S. embassy in Europe on Friday morning
and was quickly granted refugee status, said State Department
deputy spokesman Richard Boucher.
   He added, ``We certainly welcome Ms. Comaneci.''
   Asked how long she had thought about defecting, she replied, ``A
long time. I had it in my mind for a few years.''
   Comaneci has traveled abroad frequently since becoming the first
gymnast ever to score a perfect 10 at the Olympics. She won 21 gold
medals altogether in Olympic and other international meets during
her career, which earned her a life of privilege in a country that
has endured chronic shortages of consumer goods for most of this
decade.
   Her defection Tuesday to Hungary was a blow to the hard-line
government of Romanian President Nicolae Ceausescu, who had named
the gymnast a ``Hero of Socialist Labor'' for her athletic
accomplishments. Comaneci was held up as a role model for Romanian
youth.
   When asked what political impact her defection will have on
Romania, Comaneci replied: ``It's not my business.''
   The refugee status means U.S. officials believe Comaneci has a
well-founded fear of persecution if she returns to Romania, where
the government has rejected the reformist tide sweeping other East
European countries.
   Comaneci was accompanied at the news conference by a man who
appeared to be translating reporters' questions for her. She
introduced Konstantin Panit by saying: ``This is my friend who
helped me to come here. I want to thank him.''
   Her former gymnastics coach, Bela Karolyi, left Romania for the
United States in 1981 and had encouraged Comaneci earlier this week
to follow his example.
   ``I knew she was unsatisfied and unhappy about her personal
situation,'' he said. ``I was very happy to know she chose freedom
and decided to make this very difficult step.''
   Karolyi said he suspects she will be bombarded by ``business
propositions.''
   Karolyi coached the then 14-year-old Comaneci during her perfect
performances at the Montreal games.
   Speaking from Europe on Friday, Karolyi said he planned to
return to the United States on Sunday to meet with Comaneci,
possibly in Indianopolis, headquarters of the U.S. Gymnastics
Federation.
   Comaneci would be eligible to apply for permanent resident
status in the United States in one year, U.S. officials who
requested anonymity said.
   Comaneci, accompanied by six other Romanians, crossed the border
into Hungary on Tuesday and went into hiding. She reportedly told a
border guard she was leaving her homeland ``for the sake of
freedom.''
</TEXT>
