<HEAD>Oak Ridge Tritium Sales Resume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department has concluded that
amounts of a key component of nuclear warheads that had been listed
as missing weren't stolen after all, so the agency is resuming
commercial sale of the material.
   The material, tritium, has been sold for 25 years in small
amounts for research and for making glow-in-the-dark markings, as
for clock faces, exit signs and airport runway markings in remote
areas.
   It is also used to boost the power of nuclear warheads and the
power thermonuclear weapons.
   The department had suspended commercial shipments from the Oak
Ridge National Laboratory in Tennessee earlier this year after
customers complained they had not received all of the material they
had been billed for.
   Friday, the agency said it had found no evidence to support the
possibility that the material had been stolen. Deficiencies in
measurement methods were among the causes of the shipping
discrepancies, the agency said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Court Asked to Stop Exclusive Programming Rule</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Oklahoma firm is again asking a federal
appeals court to stop a rule from taking effect in January that
would let local TV stations stop cable TV systems from carrying
some syndicated shows.
   John Cole, who is representing Tulsa, Okla.-based United Video
Inc., said Friday he had petitioned the U.S. Appeals Court for the
District of Columbia to stay the implementation of new syndicated
exclusivity, or syndex, rules.
   Opponents claim the rules will cause massive headaches for cable
operators and reduce the opportunities for viewers to watch some of
their favorite TV shows.
   A three-judge panel of the court in October denied an earlier
request for a stay, and then on Nov. 17 denied the overall
challenge to the rules. Cole said he was seeking a review by the
panel or by the full court on First Amendment grounds.
   The Federal Communications Commission decided to reimpose the
rules in 1988 after an eight-year lapse.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Malaria Drug Recalled; Wrong Medicine in Bottle</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Chloroquine is CQ</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A malaria drug is being recalled by a New
Jersey company because some of the bottles instead contain an
animal diuretic.
   The recall by Biocraft Laboratories of Elmwood, N.J., applies to
Goldline brand 250 milligram chloroquine phosphate tablets packaged
in 100-tablet bottles labeled as lot number 14311, the Food and
Drug Administration said Friday.
   The recall began after a pharmacist found a bottle containing
the animal diuretic, a drug that steps up production of urine, the
FDA said. No injuries have been reported.
   Bottles containing the wrong drug have been found in California,
Utah, Arizona and Oregon.
   Using tablets from the erroneously labeled bottles would not
protect against or treat malaria, which can be life-threatening,
and large amounts of diuretics can lead to irregular heartbeat, low
blood pressure and general weakness, the agency said.
