<FIRST>r a PM-PhoneStrike     12-02 0249</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Phone Strike,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Striking NYNEX Workers Approve Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Striking telephone workers ratified a contract
negotiated last week after a four-month walkout, and planned to
return to work on Monday.
   ``It's over, it's over, it's over,'' said Bob Master, a
spokesman for the Communications Workers of America. ``We're
happy.''
   Eighty-five percent of union workers approved the contract with
Nynex Corp. The ratification Friday marked the final settlement of
strikes against regional telephone companies that began in August.
The strikes at one point involved 200,000 workers in 20 states.
   The CWA's 40,000 regional members struck Nynex subsidiary New
York Telephone. New England Telephone, another Nynex subsidiary,
was struck by 20,000 members of the International Brotherhood of
Electrical Workers.
   The IBEW settled first, and its workers returned to work last
month.
   ``We are very pleased,'' Nynex spokesman John Bonomo said, after
the CWA ratification vote. ``The settlement is fair for everyone _
customers, employees and shareholders. We're looking forward to
welcoming all our employees back to work on Monday, and dedicating
ourselves to providing the quality service our customers rely on us
for.''
   The rancorous Nynex walkout left one striker dead after a picket
line confrontation; the company reported hundreds of instances of
sabotage against its equipment. The strike created long delays for
people and companies seeking new telephone installations.
   The major point of contention concerned the company's insistence
that workers share part of their health costs. But the final
settlement did not include any health-cost sharing.
</TEXT>
