<FIRST>r a PM-CaliforniaFoxes     12-02 0245</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-California Foxes,0251</SECOND>
<HEAD>Growing Populations Of The Red Fox Has Officials Worried</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Roving bands of cunning red foxes are
outwitting Southern California officials, who worry that the
animals threaten endangered native birds and other animals.
   ``The population seems to be exploding now for some reason and
we are not sure why,'' said Larry Sitton, wildlife management
supervisor of the state Department of Fish and Game in Los Angeles.
``This has resulted in a terrible, terrible problem for native
species, pushing some to the brink of extinction.'' Red foxes have
been spotted in Torrance and El Segundo, and near the Los Angeles
International Airport. They attack endangered birds such as the
least tern and the clapper rail.
   Attempts to control the animal, which is not native to the area,
have proved futile.
   ``They are rather shy and wary of people,'' said Rudi Mattoni, a
biologist. ``The story about being foxy is no joke: They are very
difficult to catch.''
   Sarah George, a biologist with the Natural History Museum of Los
Angeles County said no one really knows how the red fox, a native
of the Sierra Nevada, got to this part of the state.
   Mattoni said despite her efforts, up to 20 species of small
animals have disappeared from the dunes just west of the airport
because of the predator's appetite.
   ``Remember how common it used to be to see rabbits on the
runways?'' Mattoni asked. ``Well, ain't no more rabbits.''
</TEXT>
