<HEAD>Talk Show Host's Harassment Suit Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for Washington talk show host John J.
McLaughlin and a former female employee who had filed a $4 million
sexual harassment and discrimination suit against him have reached
an out-of-court settlement.
   Attorneys for McLaughlin and Linda D. Dean, a former executive
assistant at McLaughlin's Oliver Productions, confirmed the
agreement Friday but refused to provide details of the confidential
settlement, The Washington Post reported today.
   McLaughlin, 60, hosts ``The McLaughlin Group,'' a political talk
show that airs weekly on 230 public television stations and four
NBC stations. He is also the host of ``One on One,'' a weekly
interview program.
   Dean's suit had described McLaughlin's office as ``a work
environment which was hostile to women'' and charged McLaughlin
with ``sexually degrading and offensive remarks and behavior ...
toward past and present female employees.''
   The suit alleged that McLaughlin fired Dean in April 1988 after
she refused to resign.
   When the suit was filed, Fred Fielding, McLaughlin's attorney,
issued a statement that said McLaughlin and his production company
``emphatically deny these bizarre and outrageous allegations.''
   McLaughlin, a former Jesuit priest and former Nixon speech
writer, has been married since 1975 to Ann Dore McLaughlin, U.S.
Secretary of Labor in the Reagan administration.
   The Post said it was unable to reach McLaughlin or Dean.
