<SECOND>PM-Mexican Elections,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Wins Mayor's Race in Matamoros; Claims Fraud Elsewhere</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOEL WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MATAMOROS, Mexico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Election officials in the Mexican state
of Tamaulipas declared an opposition candidate the winner in the
mayor's race in this border city, but his party claimed fraud in
another contest.
   In Reynosa, another border city, the campaign manager of the
Authentic Party of the Mexican Revolution accused the ruling
Institutional Revolutionary Party, or PRI, of trying to steal the
election by moving the vote count to the state capital, Ciudad
Victoria.
   Candidate Jorge Cardenas Gonzalez was declared the winner in
Matamoros, said Alfredo Davila, vice president of the State
Electoral Commission.
   Statewide mayoral elections were held Sunday, but the vote count
for Matamoros, Reynosa and other cities has been delayed by
protests, accusations of fraud and other problems.
   Davila said the results of the Reynosa mayor's race were not
complete Friday evening.
   Eliud Trevino Guerra, campaign manager for the opposition
mayoral candidate in Reynosa, Ramon Perez Garcia, said the vote
count for Reynosa had been suspiciously moved to Ciudad Victoria
after all of the opposition parties signed off on election results
showing Perez Garcia was the winner.
   Trevino claimed the PRI planned to cook the results.
   Pedro Hernandez Wilson, a PRI campaign coordinator in Reynosa,
said his party won the mayor's race in that city.
   Opposition party activists have been holding protests against
alleged PRI manipulations of the vote since before the polls even
closed. Accusations of fraud are almost routine in Mexico, where
the PRI has held most of the significant elected offices _
including every presidential administration _ since its creation 60
years ago.
