<FIRST>r a PM-Abortion-Illinois     12-02 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Abortion-Illinois,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Supreme Court Drops Illinois Abortion Case Pending Formal Settlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS CONRAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Supreme Court granted a
request from both sides in an Illinois abortion dispute to defer
arguments in the case, and a lower court was expected to approve an
out-of-court settlement.
   If it does so, it would defuse tension from a case that had been
viewed by legal experts as a likely opportunity for the high court
to alter the 1973 Roe v. Wade decision legalizing abortion.
   ``Because of this morning's action, Illinois is closer to having
a set of regulations that guarantee the health and safety of women
who choose to have an abortion,'' Illinois Attorney General Neil
Hartigan said in a statement Friday.
   The argument session in the case _ in which pro-choice advocates
opposed the state's regulations governing abortion clinics _ had
been scheduled for Tuesday, and many were awaiting the court's
ruling with considerable anticipation.
   The decision to defer arguments will keep the case on the
Supreme Court docket, in limbo, until U.S. District Judge John
Nordburg acts on a settlement reached by the two sides, and they
ask the justices to dismiss the case.
   The key issue in the Illinois dispute is a set of strict
regulations imposed on abortion clinics, where most early-pregnancy
abortions are performed.
   Opponents of the regulations, including the Illinois chapter of
the American Civil Liberties Union, which successfully had
challenged them in lower courts, said they could severely have
restricted the availability of abortions.
   ``We're gratified by the Supreme Court action in facilitating a
settlement of the lawsuit,'' said ACLU attorney Harvey Grossman.
   State Rep. Penny Pullen, a leading abortion opponent, said the
court's move came as ``no big surprise.''
   ``I am not so sure whether our interests would have been served
having Mr. Hartigan argue the case in the Supreme Court anyway,''
she said.
   Initially, Hartigan had sought to have the Supreme Court uphold
the state regulations and the high court accepted the case for
review last July 3.
   That was the same day the justices announced, in a Missouri
case, a decision giving states greater authority to regulate
abortions.
   But Hartigan, a Democratic candidate for governor in 1990, later
sought a settlement in which Illinois women would be guaranteed
continued access to abortions.
   The legal challenge to the abortion regulations was launched by
Dr. Richard Ragsdale of Rockford.
   Four years ago, Ragsdale won a preliminary injunction against
the regulations in U.S. District Court in Chicago, contending that
the state's elaborate building codes for abortion clinics were
medically unnecessary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891202-0032 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0525EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Pakistan     12-02 0505</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Says Pakistanis Frustrated After One Year of Democracy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY GANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ghulam Ishaq Khan told a
joint session of Parliament today that one year after Pakistan's
return to democracy, high expectations have turned into despair.
   He blamed most of poor public morale on the government of Prime
Minister Benazir Bhutto.
   In a toughly worded address to Pakistan's Senate and National
Assembly, Ishaq said ``A year of trading abuses and inaction is
starting to frustrate budding hopes.''
   Ishaq, 77, criticized Ms. Bhutto's left-leaning government and
its center-right political opposition for squandering opportunities
to strengthen Pakistan's fragile democracy, which followed 11 years
of military rule.
   ``Instead of understanding and accommodation there has been
confrontation at all levels and political horse trading,'' he said.
   ``A year ago there was a festive look. Faces were flushed with
fresh resolve and new hope. But now, I'm honestly reflecting the
feelings of millions of our people. They are in the grip of agony
and concern,'' Ishaq said in Urdu.
   Ms. Bhutto's Pakistan People's Party won the largest bloc of
votes in November 1988 in the first free elections in more than a
decade. But an alliance of opposition parties won control of
powerful Punjab province.
   Ishaq said bitter squabbling between the two has given rise to
the admonishment that ``the country's legislators do everything but
legislate.''
   He warned that democracy in developing nations has to be more
than an intellectual exercise. He said charges of corruption, which
have plagued Ms. Bhutto's government, and only incremental
improvements in the quality of life, will weaken ``he common man's
faith in democracy.''
   In an interview after the president's speech, Amnar Piracha, a
People's Party lawmaker, said:
   ``We have to look at what went wrong ... and people may be
upset, but people have not lost faith in the democratic process.''
   She said Ishaq, who was closely aligned with his predecessor,
military President Gen. Mohammad Zia ul-Haq, ``has to rise above
past affiliations and play a role in building (relations) between
the federal and provincial governments.''
   The majority of the Punjab lawmakers are also Zia loyalists.
Zia, who overthrew Ms. Bhutto's father in a 1977 coup, died in an
August 1988 plane crash which cleared the way for elections.
   Ishaq complained that Ms. Bhutto's government has done little to
carry on an Islamization program launched by Zia. Before his death,
Zia was trying to introduce an Islamic legal system linking state
and religion.
   Ishaq also warned against parliamentarians changing allegiance
in mid-term, which is illegal under Pakistan's constitution.
   Ms. Bhutto in November inducted three opposition members into
her cabinet, which generated opposition cries that her government
was ignoring the rules. The three, however, have maintained their
original party affiliations.
   On the positive side, the president said Ms. Bhutto's government
has launched an economic renewal program that is making some
progress, particularly in keeping the inflation rate under control.
   He said Pakistan's return to democracy has improved its
international standing and brought economic benefits.
