<FIRST>r a PM-AnnePollard     12-02 0260</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Anne Pollard,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pollard's Wife In Halfway House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who helped her husband spy on the U.S.
government for Israel is out of a federal prison in a halfway
house, prison officials said.
   Anne Henderson-Pollard had served two years and eight months of
her five-year sentence when she was released Nov. 20 from the
federal prison at Danbury, Conn., Steve Finger, acting executive
assistant at the prison, said Friday.
   Her father, Bernard R. Henderson of Secaucus, N.J., said there
was little publicity when she was moved because his daughter _ who
suffers from bilary dyskinesia, a rare gastro-intestinal disorder _
``needed a little time just to stand up. Every day she does a
little better.''
   She was sentenced in March 1987 after pleading guilty to
conspiracy to receive embezzled government property and being an
accessory after the fact to possession of state secrets.
   Her husband, Jonathan Jay Pollard, a former Navy intelligence
analyst, was sentenced to life in prison after pleading guilty to
selling secrets to Israel. He admitted selling classified
information to Israel from 1984 until his arrest in November 1985
for as much as $2,500 a month.
   Mrs. Henderson-Pollard was placed in the custody of the Women's
Prison Association and Hopper House, which maintains a halfway
house here. She is working at her father's public relations company
in Manhattan.
   Mrs. Henderson-Pollard is scheduled to be released on probation
on March 30.
   She has said she will press for her husband's release, speaking
on his behalf publicly and with U.S. and Israeli officials.
</TEXT>
