<HEAD>Weekend Snow Expected in Midwest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lake Superior snow belt braced for up to a foot of snow
today as New Mexico's north-central ski areas celebrated new
accumulations of between 8 and 12 inches and Nebraska expected wind
chills as low as 20 below by midmorning.
   A winter storm warning for heavy snow was posted today over
western and central upper Michigan, with an advisory for snow
squalls in effect for the rest of the peninsula and across
northwest Lower Michigan.
   Northwest Wisconsin is expecting the mercury to dive and up to 3
inches of fresh snow.
   In New Mexico, heavy snowfall over the north-central mountains
Friday included a foot at Angel Fire ski basin and 10 inches at Red
River.
   Strong winds with light snow peppered northern North Dakota
Friday night. Winds reached 55 mph at Devils Lake during the
evening.
   Colder temperatures, snow and strong winds are expected in
Nebraska today. A winter storm watch covered northwest and
north-central Indiana for tonight and Sunday. The storm is forecast
to leave 6 or more inches of snow.
   Snow and much colder temperatures appear headed toward
Pennsylvania and the western panhandle of West Virginia. The cold
front which marks the southeast edge of the cold air was expected
to cross portions of western Pennsylvania at about noon today.
Afternoon snow is predicted in western Pennsylvania and in the
northern portion of the West Virginia panhandle.
   Friday's high temperature for the nation was 81 degrees at San
Gabriel, Calif.
