<FIRST>r a PM-FishermenLost     12-02 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fishermen Lost,0301</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search for Lobstermen Ended After 11 Days</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Coast Guard gave up its search for five
missing lobstermen after nine days of searching amid snow and fog
over thousands of miles of the Atlantic.
   The hunt for the Heidi Marie and its crew of five was officially
suspended at 5 p.m. Friday. Hundreds of men and women and the Navy,
Air National Guard and even Air Force B-52s from Michigan had taken
part.
   Despite sightings of at least five flares that signaled life
somewhere out in the vast cold sea, neither the boat nor its crew
have been seen or heard from since Nov. 22.
   ``It's a very difficult conclusion to reach, but we've come to
the point where our chances of success are about nil,'' said Rear
Admiral Richard Rybacki, commander of the First Coast Guard
District in Boston, headquarters for the search for the 72-foot
steel-hulled vessel out of Stonington, Conn.
   Aircraft and cutters were deployed over more than 100,000 square
miles in the search.
   ``We feel awful,'' Coast Guard spokesman Steve Aitkins said.
``It is frustrating. You do all you can. It's frustrating for us.
We want to give everybody good news.''
   The last sign of life came Thursday when a Navy plane spotted an
orange object the size of a life raft about 4 feet under water, 300
miles south of Nantucket.
   On Friday, high winds, snow, fog and roiling seas hindered
efforts to get another glimpse of the object.
   The crew included the captain, Mark Middleton, 33, of Norwich,
Conn.; Michael Hare, 22, of Pawcatuck, Conn., Kenneth Raymond
Gould, 20, and Ray Morris III, 19, both of Westerly, R.I., and
Arthur Banks, 25, of Ashaway, R.I.
</TEXT>
