<HEAD>Subway Gunman A No-Show For Questioning In $50 Million Suit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for one of the four youths shot by
subway gunman Bernard Goetz demanded a judge declare Goetz the
loser in a $50 million lawsuit after he failed to appear for a
deposition hearing.
   ``Basically, the man's a coward when he doesn't have a gun with
him,'' Ron Kuby said. ``He has absolutely no respect for his legal
obligations.''
   Kuby and the other lawyer, William Kunstler, filed the motion
for sanctions against Goetz in Bronx Supreme Court on Friday in the
lawsuit brought by Darrell Cabey.
   The motion will be heard Dec. 18 by a judge to be appointed at
that time, Kunstler said.
   A request for comment left on Goetz's telephone answering
machine drew no response.
   Cabey and three companions, Barry Allen, Troy Canty and James
Ramseur, all teen-agers at the time, were shot by Goetz when they
approached him in a subway car Dec. 22, 1984. Goetz said they
intended to rob him; they said they were panhandling.
   Kuby said that Cabey, paralyzed and brain-damaged by one of
Goetz's bullets, has been declared incompetent and unable to give
testimony.
   Goetz, 42, was acquitted of attempted murder but found guilty of
a weapon law violation, for which he eventually served eight months.
   Several civil suits against Goetz have been pending in the
Bronx, brought by Cabey for $50 million, Canty for $5 million, and
Ramseur for $8.5 million.
