<FIRST>r i PM-Summit-Bush 3rdLd-Writethru a0477 12-02 0626</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit-Bush, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0477,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Splits Time Between Summit Plans, Monitoring Philippine Conflict</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New Bush quotes in top 4 grafs, picks up 4th graf pvs, ``White
House xxx''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, feeling ``pretty
good'' despite rough seas, received an update early today on the
coup attempt in the Philippines before embarking on his first
summit with Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev.
   High seas and gale-force winds forced a change in the site of
today's U.S.-Soviet talks to the Maxim Gorky, a Soviet cruise ship
anchored off Malta, and cancellation of the opening summit
ceremonies. But the talks began as scheduled.
   Bush took the admiral's barge from the USS Belknap, his summit
residence, to the Maxim Gorky, where he was met by Gorbachev. The
two leaders shook hands, and Bush told Gorbachev, ``Let's go to
work.''
   He told reporters he was ``feeling pretty good'' and that he
slept ``fine, just fine ... piece of cake.''
   White House officials said Bush awoke at 7 a.m. this morning
and, at a breakfast meeting, was given a detailed report on the
situation in the Philippines by Secretary of State James A. Baker
III, White House chief of staff John Sununu and Brent Scowcroft,
the national security adviser.
   In Manila, renewed fighting was reported today as government
warplanes and helicopters hit remaining rebel positions. Rebels
were reported still holding an air base in the central Philippines,
and hundreds were gathered outside armed forces headquarters in
Manila and in the city's financial district. But the Aquino
government said the coup attempt had been defeated.
   Since arriving in Malta early Friday, Bush has divided his time
between preparations for his meetings with Gorbachev and updates on
the attempt by rebel military officials to topple the government of
Corazon Aquino. Bush, at the request of Mrs. Aquino, ordered U.S.
fighter jets Friday to provide air cover and help the government
defend against the coup attempt.
   Bush was already over the Atlantic Ocean on his way to Malta
when Mrs. Aquino asked for U.S. air cover to halt rebel air attacks
and keep the mutineers pinned down in two air bases they
controlled. A few hours earlier, the rebels had bombed the
presidential palace in the most serious effort to bring down Mrs.
Aquino since she came to power in 1986.
   The president approved the request from aboard Air Force One at
12:30 p.m. Manila time (11:30 p.m. EDT), and the decision was
relayed to Mrs. Aquino an hour later from Washington by Vice
President Dan Quayle, said Roman Popadiuk, deputy press secretary.
   ``The process went well under very difficult circumstances,''
Popadiuk said, noting that the request came late at night while
Bush and Secretary of State James A. Baker III were both in flight.
   In addition to the Air Force F-4 Phantom jets providing air
cover, 100 Marines were sent from a U.S. base to protect the U.S.
Embassy in Manila, Popadiuk said.
   ``There are no reports of any injuries to Americans, or any
attacks on Americans,'' he said.
   In Washington, Pentagon spokesman Pete Williams said no U.S.
planes had ``fired any shots or intercepted any rebel aircraft.''
   Even limited U.S. military intervention could give Gorbachev a
rejoinder to complaints Bush planned to lodge about Soviet military
involvement in Afghanistan, El Salvador, Nicaragua and elsewhere.
   Arkady Maslennikov, a spokesman for the Supreme Soviet,
criticized Bush's decision.
   ``Any interference in internal developments, especially by
outside powers, is destructive and leads to deterioration of the
situation,'' he said. ``In any event, the best thing is to allow
the Filipinos themselves to sort it out.''
   Popadiuk said Bush's motive was twofold: ``A democratic
government has asked for assistance; we have American lives to
protect.''
</TEXT>
