<FIRST>r i PM-Soviet-Unrest     12-02 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviet-Unrest,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenian Legislature Votes to Annex Karabakh</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Armenian legislature has voted to annex a
disputed region in a neighboring republic, an activist said today,
in a move that defied the federal government and could cause
further ethnic violence.
   The lawmakers claimed the region, the Nagorno-Karabakh enclave,
on Friday after the national parliament asked Armenia's neighbor,
the republic of Azerbaijan, to quell tensions over the area, the
activist said.
   The Armenian Supreme Soviet and the National Council of
Nagorno-Karabakh informed the national government of the
annexation, the activist, Karen Shakhbazyan, said in a telephone
interview.
   The national government probably will not recognize the action,
taken in the Armenian capital, Yerevan.
   Nagorno-Karabakh's population is predominantly ethnic Armenian
and Christian, but the mountainous region is located in Azerbaijan,
which is mostly Moslem. Despite being called a Soviet autonomous
region, the enclave is supposed to obey the Azerbaijani government
in Baku.
   Unconfirmed reports earlier in the week said three people were
killed in violence stemming from the dispute, adding to dozens who
have been killed in the past 18 months.
   Shakhbazyan, speaking from Yerevan, said many Armenian deputies
will boycott the second session of the national Congress of
People's Deputies which begins Dec. 12 in Moscow.
   He accused Azerbaijan of imposing a new rail blockade on Armenia
like the one that halted shipment of fuel, food and other goods
this fall.
   No trains had arrived from Nakhichivan, a small area of
Azerbaijan sandwiched between Armenia and Iran, since Nov. 28, he
said. Trains were arriving on schedule from the Georgian republic
in the north, he reported.
   The Armenian population, citing what they call years of willful
neglect by Azerbaijan, began demanding in February 1988 that
Armenia annex Nagorno-Karabakh area.
   Mosow has rejected that demand, and in January it imposed direct
rule through a commission headed by Arkady Volsky.
   On Tuesday, the final day of the national Supreme Soviet's fall
session, legislators replaced the Volsky commission with a
legislative oversight commission.
   The Supreme Soviet also ordered Azerbaijan to work with local
officials in Nagorno-Karabakh to restore order. In the meantime,
Interior Ministry soldiers are to stay in the area.
   Azerbaijani activists have expressed displeasure with the
decision as well.
   Ekhtibar Mamedov, leader of the Azerbaijan People's Front
political movement, claimed there was a secret provision in the
Supreme Soviet declaration that prevents Azerbaijan from
interfering in Armenia's affairs.
</TEXT>
