<FIRST>r a PM-DayWithoutArt 1stLd-Writethru a0440 12-02 0705</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Day Without Art, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0440,0715</SECOND>
<HEAD>Museums Mourn Loss of Artists to AIDS Across Nation</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to add location of museum, which is in New York.
Minor editing elsewhere.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PATRICIA BIBBY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of museums and galleries throughout the country
observed AIDS Awareness Day by holding memorial services,
temporarily removing art masterpieces to symbolize the disease's
ravages in the arts community.
   ``The point of `A Day Without Art' is to refer metaphorically to
loss and to try to get more people as concerned with the loss from
AIDS as it is often, with, say, earthquakes and other tragedies
that occur,'' said Philip Yenawine, director of education at the
Museum of Modern Art in New York and co-chairman of the nationwide
project.
   Some 600 art institutions participated in the Friday observance,
organizers said. A group of arts professionals called Visual AIDS
organized ``A Day Without Art'' to coincide with the World Health
Organization's second AIDS Awareness Day.
   Elsewhere, nearly 80 people were arrested in a protest in
Washington and New England corporate leaders convened in Boston to
discuss how the business world can better respond to the AIDS
epidemic.
   In New York, numerous art galleries closed for the day or
temporarily darkened their halls. At the Metropolitan Museum of
Art, Picasso's ``Portrait of Gertrude Stein'' was removed and a
placard was put in its place to explain the loss the art community
is experiencing because of AIDS.
   Elizabeth Taylor, chairwoman of the American Foundation for AIDS
Research, told reporters at the Museum of Modern Art that the
observance was just a small reminder of the plague, ``and everybody
in this world needs to be reminded time and time again.''
   At a 14th Street subway station, artist Ross Lewis encouraged
people to put the names of dead friends on index cards and tape
them to black paper with which he had covered a colorful mural.
   About 100 demonstrators marched in front of the New York office
of the Immigration and Naturalization Service to protest the U.S.
policy of forcing HIV-infected immigrants to get a special waiver.
   At the University of Maine Museum of Art in Orono, workers
draped the artwork in black.
   ``There are huge social losses and artistic losses in the art
world'' because of AIDS, said Charles Shepard, museum director.
   Similar observances were held in Atlanta, where the Arts
Exchange gallery was closed; in Pittsburgh, where lights were
dimmed for 10 minutes at the Carnegie Museum of Art; in Seattle,
where large black shrouds were hung over many downtown sculptures;
and in Los Angeles, where visitors to the Museum of Contemporary
Art and the County Museum of Art found the usual admission fees
waived and were asked instead to donate to the AIDS Project Los
Angeles.
   In New Orleans, the NO-AIDS task force displayed children's
artistic conception of AIDS. One simply had the word ``choose''
between the words ``AIDS'' and ``life,'' said Lisa Lee, a member of
the task force.
   In Washington, nearly 80 demonstrators were arrested Friday
after they sat down on Pennsylvania Avenue in front of the White
House to protest what they called the government's lack of
leadership in the AIDS epidemic.
   Those taking part in the civil disobedience were among some 200
people who attended an earlier rally criticizing President Bush for
what they said was the government's inadequate support for AIDS
research and services.
   At a conference at Boston's World Trade Center, business leaders
attended a variety of seminars on how to deal with acquired immune
deficiency syndrome in the workplace.
   ``A lot more things like these need to be done,'' said William
Baumhaur, president of the Fuddruckers hamburger chain and keynote
speaker at the conference. ``Every business will be impacted by
AIDS. We can't ignore it.''
   As of the end of October, the federal Centers for Disease
Control in Atlanta had recorded 112,241 cases of AIDS in the United
States, with 66,493 deaths.
   AIDS is caused by a virus that damages the body's immune system,
leaving victims susceptible to infections and cancer. It is spread
most often through sexual contact, needles or syringes shared by
drug abusers, infected blood or blood products, and from pregnant
women to their offspring.
</TEXT>
