<FIRST>r i PM-Mandela     12-02 0178</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mandela,0185</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Declines to Say When Mandela Will Be Freed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YAMOUSSOUKRO, Ivory Coast (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President F.W. de Klerk of
South Africa said today that imprisoned black nationalist Nelson
Mandela will be freed but he declined to say when.
   De Klerk also said reforms undertaken by his government were
being recognized by African and other foreign governments.
   ``There is a spirit of hope, and people are reaching out for
each other in South Africa,'' he said.
   Speaking at a news conference after a day of talks with Ivorian
President Felix Houphouet-Boigny, de Klerk said: ``As and when it
is possible, he (Mandela) will be released.''
   He declined to elaborate.
   De Klerk said he hopes to establish full diplomatic relations
with Ivory Coast, whose president has praised his reforms but has
insisted that Mandela be released before relations can be
established.
   ``I don't think it is a dream. It can become a reality,'' de
Klerk said.
   He said he wouldn't speculate on the timing of such a move,
because the Ivorian government must make its own decision.
</TEXT>
