<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0940EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Salvador     12-02 0395</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Salvador,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Refugees Mission Pulls Out of El Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A United Nations mission to
help civil war refugees fled after its office was smashed and its
members were threatened.
   Gonzalo Perez, the chief U.N. representative here, said the
mission of about 30 members was evacuated Friday ``for lack of
guarantees'' and that the office will be transferred to Guatemala.
   The program was administered by UNICEF to help people displaced
by the decade-old war between leftist guerrillas and government
troops and to sponsor development programs.
   The U.N. office in Escalon was damaged Wednesday when guerrillas
invaded it and the adjoining affluent section of San Benito on the
city's west side.
   Employees inside the building were evacuated by the Green Cross,
an organization similar to the Red Cross, during a lull in the
fighting.
   Government troops entered the U.N. office later, Perez said, and
an inspection on Thursday, after the guerrillas pulled out of the
area, showed extensive destruction.
   The front of the building was pocked with bullet holes, and
equipment and furniture inside appeared to have been deliberately
smashed, Perez said.
   President Alfredo Cristiani's rightist government did not admit
responsibility for the damage. But Ernesto Ferreiro, the Foreign
Ministry's protocol chief, said he extended apologies to Perez on
behalf of Cristiani.
   On Thursday, more than 240 Americans were evacuated, most from
the Escalon-San Benito area. They included private citizens and
U.S. Embassy personnel and dependents.
   On Friday, Eloy Guevara, a photo stringer working for Agence
France-Presse, was killed by gunfire after a clash between
guerrillas and government soldiers in the working-class district of
Soyapango.
   Guevara, 27, was the 18th journalist killed since the war began
in late 1979 and the second since the guerrillas launched an
all-out attack, in phases, on the capital Nov. 11.
   Two reporters at the scene said Guevara was hit by assault rifle
fire as he crossed an intersection with three Red Cross workers,
and the fire came from the side of the street controlled by air
force paratroopers.
   Guerrillas had withdrawn from positions on the other side of the
street more than an hour before, and military officers on the scene
had given the Red Cross workers the go-head to proceed, the
witnesses said.
   Both insisted on not being identified by name for fear of
reprisals.
</TEXT>
