<FIRST>u i PM-Taiwan-Elections 1stLd-Writethru   12-02 0653</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Taiwan-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0468,0674</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vote-Buying Reported in Taiwan's First Democratic Election</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with early leaders and more on fraud.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNIE HUANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two candidates who want Taiwan to reassess
its relationship with China took early leads today in this nation's
first democratic election. Officials reported widespread
vote-buying.
   Long lines of voters waited to cast ballots, and state radio
reported a heavy turnout to choose legislators, municipal and
county officials. Tens of thousands of police guarded polling
places to prevent violence.
   The election was expected to mark a major step in Taiwan's march
toward democracy after four decades of rule by the Nationalists,
who lost a civil war to Communist forces on the Chinese mainland in
1949. It was the first election to include opposition candidates
and will test the opposition Democratic Progressive Party,
legalized at the end of martial law in 1987.
   Results were expected early Sunday. In all, 722 candidates ran
in the legislative, mayoral and county races.
   The Nationalists cannot lose all power in the election. The
256-seat Legislature and the electoral college are dominated by
elderly Nationalists elected for life on the Chinese mainland in
the late 1940s to support the party's claim that it is the
legitimate government of all China.
   The electoral college will choose a president next year.
   The most contentious campaign issue involved some opposition
calls for Taiwan's independence, a seditious act under Taiwan's
constitution. Communist China has threatened to invade Taiwan if it
declares independence.
   In one Taipei district, candidate Yeh Chu-lan, an independence
activist, was among the leaders for a seat in the legislature.
   Mrs. Yeh is the widow of Cheng Nan-Rong, who killed himself in
April to avoid a police investigation for advocating independence
for Taiwan. In her campaign, Mrs. Yeh continued her husband's work
and risks prosecution.
   Incomplete results indicated that Jaw Shau-kong, a popular
Nationalist legislator, was far ahead in his Taipei district. Jaw
has pushed for political reform, calling for the retirement of
aging legislators and negotiations with the Communist government in
Beijing.
   In the industrial city of Kaohsiung, Hsu Hsiao-dan, a former
dancer, model and painter, was behind. Ms. Hsu called for universal
love and freedom in her campaign and distributed nude photos of
herself.
   The Independence Evening News today reported large-scale
distribution of ``silver bullets,'' or bribes, before campaigning
ended Friday.
   ``Some candidates threw down big bucks,'' it said.
   The paper's sister publication, the Independence Morning News,
was sued for libel by the Nationalist Party Friday after it accused
the Nationalists of vote-buying.
   Financial officials have said cash in circulation jumped by $1.1
billion in the past week because of vote-buying.
   During balloting today several voters told The Associated Press
they had sold their votes.
   One voter said she sold her and her husband's vote to a
Nationalist candidate for $19 each. Other voters said that was the
going price, although one women said she only received $8 for her
vote.
   A spokesman for the Central Election Commission reported scores
of cases of vote-buying and intimidation.
   The spokesman, Ho En-pao, said investigations were under way and
that evidence had been found in several cases. He did not disclose
which party was to blame.
   In the only report of violence, a fight broke out in the
northwestern city of Hualian after opposition candidates
photographed a man voting on behalf of an elderly man. State radio
said the elderly man's hands were shaking so he needed help.
Election officials said the case was under investigation.
   Taiwan's three government TV stations initially gave almost
exclusive coverage to Nationalist candidates but yielded under
pressure from the public.
   The opposition claimed the Nationalists were helped by an
immense party machine that mobilized village chiefs and other
politicians to secure votes.
   Nationalists had also been accused of sabotaging opposition
office and shooting an independent candidate. The Nationalists
denied the charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
