<FIRST>r i AM-Sudan     12-02 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sudan,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Senior Politicians Released from Prison to House Arrest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government released from prison two
senior politicians jailed since a June 30 military coup but is
keeping them under house arrest, a government source and their
associates said Saturday.
   An official source, who refused to be further identified,
confirmed a newspaper report on the disposition of Hassan Turabi,
head of the fundamentalist National Islamic Front, and Mohamed
Osman Mirghani, head of the centrist Democratic Unionist Party.
   The source would give no further details, but followers of the
two said they were transferred from Kober Prison in suburban
Khartoum. Several politicians remain incarcerated at the prison,
chief among them the ousted prime minister, Sadek el-Mahdi of the
Umma Party.
   The official newspaper Al-Sudan Al-Hadith said Turabi and
Mirghani were released ``after they voiced their support for the
revolution'' and the policies of the military government, which
include disbanding Sudan's 36 political parties.
   ``They have not been implicated in recent communist plots aiming
to undermine the revolution,'' the newspaper said.
   That seemed to indicate the ruling junta is implicating el-Mahdi
and Mohamed Ibrahim Nugud, secretary-general of the Communist
Party, both still in prison, in a week-long strike by doctors. The
government has blamed communists for the illegal strike.
   In addition to the parties, coup leader Lt. Gen. Omar Hassan
el-Bashir disbanded all the country's professional associations and
trade unions. He jailed most senior government officials and vowed
to try them on charges of political and economic corruption.
   Only a handful have been put on trial. The government says about
20 officials remain in detention, but informed sources put the
figure at close to 100.
</TEXT>
