<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Bulgaria     12-02 0216</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Bulgaria,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Calls on New Bulgarian Leaders To Clear Up Markov Murder</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain has called on the new Bulgarian leadership
to clear up the murder of Georgi Markov, the Bulgarian defector
killed in London 11 years ago by poison injected through the tip of
an umbrella.
   Foreign Office Minister William Waldegrave told the House of
Commons on Friday that the hard-line Bulgarian government led by
Todor Zhivkov, which was toppled Nov. 10, was ``the instigator'' of
the murder.
   With a new government led by Petur Mladenov now in power, he
said, the truth about Markov's murder must be told.
   Annabel Markov, the defector's widow, was quoted Saturday as
telling The Times of London she hoped the reforms sweeping Bulgaria
and Eastern Europe would help reveal the truth about her husband's
death.
   ``I have always believed evil does not go unpunished. There is
real hope now that my husband's killer may be tracked down,'' she
was quoted as saying.
   Mrs. Markov is convinced the Bulgarian secret police have a file
on her husband, The Times said.
   Markov defected in 1969 and received death threats after
broadcasting a series of programs in 1977 attacking Bulgaria's
Communist government on the British Broadcasting Corp. world
service. He was murdered on a London street in 1978.
</TEXT>
