<FIRST>u i AM-EastBlocNotebook Bjt   12-02 1016</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-East Bloc Notebook, Bjt,1042</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Month That Ended An Era ^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR's NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Alison Smale, AP chief of bureau in Vienna, has
covered the East bloc, Germany and the Soviet Union for a decade.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The panic in the eyes of a man
grabbed by riot police. Shabby East German Trabants and sleek West
German Mercedes side by side on the Kurfuerstendamm in West Berlin
after the Berlin Wall crumbled. The explosion of joy in Wenceslas
Square when the hated leaders that suppressed the Prague Spring
reforms 20 years ago had to step down.
   Those are some of the lasting images of a turbulent month that
ended an era in Eastern Europe. Millions of people demanded a say
in politics and took their fear, their courage and their joy into
the streets.
   Here are some images of that breathtaking month:
   Oct. 28: Beloved Prague, city of a thousand spires, marred again
by hundreds of riot police hounding peaceful pro-democracy
demonstrators down alleys and sidestreets.
   Wenceslas Square, a tree-lined boulevard at the heart of the
city, resembles a police camp.
   A hapless Pole tries to explain to a police officer he is on the
square by mistake. Suddenly, a riot policeman charges, slams him
against a wall and beats him in a display of the kind of violence
that kept East Europeans in check most of the last four decades.
   Nov. 3-4: In Prague again, but East Germans are the drama.
Thousands of them cram into the West German Embassy, another wave
of East Germans heading West through Hungary and Czechoslovakia.
Amid the jubilation, a prescient diplomat, scarcely believing he
could be right, mutters, ``The wall has gone.''
   Nov. 5: Pomezi, a Czech village sandwiched between East and West
Germany. A chill dawn beside the dilapidated church.
   Scores of East German Trabant cars arrive at the border every
hour, carrying their occupants away from a lifetime under
communism. A Leipzig worker tells how he got caught in the Dresden
train station on the bloody night of Oct. 3-4 and saw riot police
beating back thousands trying to get aboard trains carrying East
Germans to the West.
   ``I saw them beat children,'' he says. ``That was when my wife
and I decided to leave. We were always told the DDR (East Germany)
was a state of peace.''
   Nov. 6: Bratislava, Czechoslovakia, in the rain. Another side of
repression. In court, Jan Carnogursky, a Slovak dissident, facing
up to 10 years in jail over just one article in an underground
newspaper.
   Breaking through the barrier of fear that keeps most people far
from the courtroom, a crowd of 200 gathers in the name of freedom
under the watchful eyes of uniformed police and plainclothes
officers who film them from the window.
   Later, activists talk warmly of the popular revolt in East
Germany. Soon, soon, they say, it must come to Czechoslovakia.
   Nov. 9-10: East and West Berlin. A night of delirium as the
Berlin Wall really does open. For this moment, there are no words.
Car horns honk and people scream, weep and embrace. Even hardened
West Berlin punkers have tears in their eyes.
   An East German family sharing my 2 a.m. taxi ride around a city
they haven't seen for 28 years is dumbstruck. What the mother
really couldn't believe, as we inched our way through the Trabants
around Bahnhof Zoo, was that fresh flowers were on sale in the
middle of the night.
   Nov. 13: Leipzig. First taste of the center of the East German
revolution, when 200,000 people roar across Karl Marx Square, ``We
are the people!'' Everyone is there _ young and old, religious
believers and Communists, students and workers.
   ``I'll be here until we have free elections,'' says a
70-year-old woman, with the unbending Teutonic resolve that has
powered the revolt. ``We are the generation that was most betrayed.
Maybe the children will have it better.''
   Nov. 17: Leipzig. New fears replace the old. An ethnic German
family who abandoned a prosperous farm in Romania 25 years ago sits
at home, worrying. Will the opening of the borders mean a currency
reform? ``We'll lose everything again,'' shudders the mother, two
years away from a meager East German pension with only savings in
East German marks to rely on.
   Nov. 20: Prague as people dreamed to see it ever since the day
the 1968 ``Prague Spring'' was over, crushed by Warsaw Pact troops
and tanks. More than 100,000 people are on the streets saying ``No
more!'' to police brutality and Stalinist rule.
   The procession is an explosion of Czech wit, pride and joy. A
friend leaps toward me and his wife, hugging us tight with
happiness. ``We made it,'' he cries.
   Nov. 24: Alexander Dubcek returns triumphantly to Prague after
19 years in the political wilderness. On a balcony, Dubcek bows to
the cheers, smiling broadly his hands outstretched in thanks. Then,
he reaches toward the crowd and makes a movement as if to draw the
300,000 people to his breast. The vast crowd goes mad with joy. A
day later, a photograph capturing the moment goes up in the windows
of the state news agency.
   Nov. 27. Wenceslas Square is a sea of people and national flags
and even the clocks stop for the noontime general strike, the
biggest protest against 41 years of Communist rule.
   Hundreds of thousands sway like a huge soccer crowd as they
derisively chant the name of Miroslav Stepan, the sacked Prague
party boss they blame for past police brutality.
   ``We'll be so happy if we can have back the people who had to
leave this country,'' exults a villager from north Bohemia, in
Prague for the past week to drink in the most exciting days of the
revolution. ``Everybody's expecting to spend Christmas together.''
   ``What fascinates me,'' says a woman, ``is how all of a sudden
people like each other.'' She is standing 50 feet from the spot
where, just a month ago _ an era ago _ the policeman beat the Pole.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
