<FIRST>u i PM-SummitRdp 13thLd-Writethru a0549 12-02 0961</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit Rdp, 13th Ld-Writethru, a0549,930</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush and Gorbachev Discuss Wide Range of Topics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 4th graf to UPDATE with weather-related delay in start-up
of afternoon round of talks.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and Mikhail S.
Gorbachev began a storm-tossed summit today with five hours of
talks, and the White House said afterward the two men worked in a
``spirit of forward-looking cooperation.''
   The president and his Soviet counterpart ``recognized that
economic and political challenges were ahead for Eastern Europe,
and vowed to consider the opportunities presented with sensitivity
and firm initiative,'' said the statement issued by White House
spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   High winds and rough seas forced the two men to scrap plans to
talk aboard a Soviet naval vessel anchored off-shore, opting
instead for a session on a docked Soviet cruise liner that served
as Gorbachev's headquarters for the two-day summit.
   Bush returned to his headquarters on the USS Belknap following
the initial sessions. The White House said an afternoon round of
talks were put on hold because of the bad weather, which kept Bush
from immediately leaving the Belknap.
   The White House said they talked ``almost continuously'' for
nearly five hours, including a session with aides and a session
with only note-takers, and then continued their talks over lunch.
   ``President Bush spoke for more than an hour to open the
meeting, laying out more than a dozen ideas for economic and
political progress in U.S.-Soviet relations,'' the statement said.
   ``The discussion ranged from the economic situation in Eastern
Europe to arms control and Central America. Chairman Gorbachev
spoke at length of perestroika and the goals of his reform
program,'' it said.
   The two men also arranged to have an afternoon of talks before
getting together for dinner. The summit concludes on Sunday.
   The White House said the opening talks included a `'very
productive, informal and substantive meeting.''
   ``The meetings were sparked by a spirit of forward-looking
cooperation during these increasingly changing times,'' it said.
   The White House said the discussion ranged from the economic
situation in Eastern Europe to arms control and Central America.
``Chairman Gorbachev spoke at length of perestroika and the goals
of his reform program,'' it said.
   ``The president emphasized his support for the success of
perestroika. He set forth his ideas as a broad framework for
actions that would help the two nations work together for peace and
prosperity,'' it said.
   The two leaders, both in an affable mood, met aboard the
25,000-ton Maxim Gorky, which is Gorbachev's headquarters for the
weekend summit, to begin nearly 12 hours of scheduled talks that
could bring down the curtain on the Cold War.
   ``I think we've got a very good beginning of the dialogue ... an
excellent beginning,'' Secretary of State James A. Baker III told
reporters after Bush and Gorbachev completed their initial
three-hour session.
   Senior Soviet officials said Gorbachev wants the summit to
produce a timetable for completing U.S.-Soviet treaties on reducing
strategic nuclear weapons, conventional forces in central Europe
and chemical weapons.
   These officials, who spoke only on condition they not be
identified, said Gorbachev will convene a meeting of Warsaw Pact
leaders in Moscow on Monday to discuss the results of the two-day
summit. Bush will spend Monday briefing allied leaders at NATO
headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
   Gorbachev and Bush were smiling and in high spirits as they
clasped hands across a long rectangular table, measuring barely a
yard across.
   ``It's so narrow that if we don't have enough arguments, we'll
kick each other,'' Gorbachev told Bush.
   Asked by reporters if they would reach any agreements, Gorbachev
replied, `` da, da (yes, yes).'' Agreement on what? he was asked.
``Mnogovo,'' which was translated as meaning ``a lot of things.''
   When Bush was asked the same question, the president echoed
Gorbachev. ``Mnogovo,'' he said.
   The two leaders met in the plush surroundings of a library-like
room known as the Card Room, next to the ship's lounge and
nightclub, on the Maxim Gorky's promenade deck.
   They sat in deep captain's chairs, accompanied by aides on
either side.
   Arms control, East-West trade and the breathtaking democratic
reforms sweeping communist Eastern Europe dominated the agenda for
the Bush-Gorbachev talks. Both leaders said they hoped their
discussions would strengthen long-term prospects for world peace
and European unity.
   Gorbachev, asked if he would discuss fast-moving political
changes in East Europe, replied, ``We'll be discussing everything,
including that.''
   The senior Soviet sources said Gorbachev wants a Stategic Arms
Reduction Treaty ready for signing at his next planned summit
meeting with Bush in Washington next spring or early summer.
   They said the Soviet leader also is seeking a Bush commitment to
attend a 35-nation summit at the end of 1990 to sign a separate
accord sharply reducing U.S. and Soviet troops in central Europe.
   The original site for the first summit session was the Soviet
guided missile cruiser Slava, anchored near the Belknap in this
harbor, but White House officials said the meeting was shifted to
the Maxim Gorky because gale-force winds would have made launch
transfers treacherous.
   The White House said ``there was no danger to anyone aboard
Belknap as a result of the high winds.''
   The 630-foot Maxim Gorky is about twice as large as the Slava in
total tonnage. Built 20 years ago in West Germany, it was sold to
the Soviet Union in 1974 and is used frequently for cruises through
the North Sea and Scandanavian waters. The vessel was repaired
after it rammed an iceberg off Norway last June with 900 people
aboard, but there were no injuries.
   The two leaders are scheduled to meet Sunday aboard the Belknap,
flagship of the U.S. Sixth Fleet which is anchored about 400 yards
from the Slava.
</TEXT>
