<FIRST>r i PM-SummitColor 5thLd-Writethru a0541 12-02 0922</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Summit Color, 5th Ld-Writethru, a0541,890</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gale Winds Force Change in Summit Site</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Top 4 grafs new with second session delayed; picks up 4th graf
pvs, ``Maltese meteorologist xxx'' Edits to tighten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Winds gusting to 48 miles per hour
and roiling seas moved the first summit session between President
Bush and Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev to a Soviet luxury
liner and delayed the second round of meetings.
   Bush and Gorbachev met this morning on the 25,000-ton liner
Maxim Gorky after gale-force winds caused both the Soviet ship
Slava, the original site of today's meeting, and the USS Belknap to
drag their anchors.
   Bush returned to Belknap after five hours of talks and was to
return to the Gorky for an afternoon summit session. But the White
House said the weather forced a delay in that second session.
   This morning, the White House issued a statement saying that the
winds, which built overnight, ``make it difficult to disembark from
launches at the Slava and the Belknap. Therefore, this morning's
meeting has been shifted to the Soviet ship Gorky at anchor at
Malta.''
   Maltese meteorologist Spiro Agius said the winds should abate by
Sunday, the final day of the summit. ``It will definitely be
improving tomorrow,'' he said.
   Despite a little pitching from the heavy seas, the winds did not
present a danger to anyone on the Belknap, Bush's headquarters for
the summit and the site of his wrap-up meeting on Sunday with
Gorbachev, the White House statement said.
   In fact, Bush, who slept aboard the Belknap Friday night, said
on the Gorky that he was ``feeling pretty good.'' Asked how he
slept, he said, ``fine, just fine...piece of cake.''
   The stormy conditions prompted Raisa Gorbachev to delay a
sightseeing tour, but she later went ahead with the visit,
including an inspection of a 16th-century cathedral.
   ``This is the type of weather that shipwrecked Saint Paul on
these rocks. We usually have this in February,'' Joe Cassar,
Maltese minister for housing, told a rain-soaked crowd that had
gathered to see the Soviet leader's wife at Santa Lucia, a suburb
of Valletta, the capital city.
   Both the 12,500-ton Slava and 8,600-ton Belknap are anchored in
the middle of the Bay, while the much larger Gorky, which has been
Gorbachev's base during his time in Malta, is tied up at a pier.
   The high winds were blowing from the northeast. Marsaxlokk Bay,
a large indentation in the southeast coast of Malta, is exposed to
winds from easterly directions.
   The hasty change in plans for the superpower meeting in the
Mediterranean came as the tiny wind-whipped island nation was as
ready as it would ever be for its weekend in the international
limelight.
   Malta was hoping the summit would boost attention for the
island, but the bad weather probably was not the type of publicity
the Maltese had in mind.
   On shore, red Soviet flags flapped in the stiff breeze.
   On Friday, street salesmen were out in force to hawk
commemorative T-shirts and other souvenir and residents strolled to
the edge of Marsaxlokk Bay for a look at the two anchored warships.
   ``This may help your tourism,'' Bush had told Prime Minister
Edward Fenech-Adami on Friday following his arrival from Washington.
   ``It will probably bring positive economic effects,'' said a
21-year-old woman who identified herself only as Dorothy, assessing
the summit's meaning for the 350,000 Maltese.
   She and two companions had come out Friday night for a glimpse
of the warships. ``We were bored,'' she admitted.
   On the other side of the bay, in the fishing village of
Birzebuga, Albert Roberts led a group of Labor Party workers
preparing for a peace demonstration timed to coincide with the
summit, decorating a float that will be a part of a 60-piece parade
on Saturday.
   ``Give peace a chance,'' said signs on the float in both English
and Russian.
   Although Bush and Gorbachev were unlikely to see the parade
itself, Roberts said: ``Malta is ready to show to the world that we
hope for peace.''
   Traffic circles and seaside roads were decorated with Soviet and
U.S. flags, and Maltese security forces stood through the night in
clumps of two or three on streets overlooking the harbor.
   Malta's entire 1,200-man military and most of its 1,000 police
officers have been assigned to the summit security job. Roadblocks
and checkpoints made it hard to get around on the narrow island
roads, although it seemed anyone with a good story could get waved
through.
   Although thousands of Maltese had skipped work or classes to
catch a glimpse of Bush's arrival early Friday, most were already
in bed by the time Gorbachev's Il-62 rolled up to the airport
gangway at 11 p.m. sharp during a gentle mist.
   The prime minister and his cabinet broke from their line and
walked over to the plane's gangplank as Sgt. Emmanuel Gatt, a
32-veteran of the Maltese army, and two other soldiers rolled out a
red carpet for Gorbachev and his wife Raisa, who walked arm-in-arm
down the steps.
   After a 21-gun salute, a Maltese armed forces band in dark blue
uniforms with red piping on their pants played the Soviet and
Maltese national anthems.
   Gorbachev thanked Malta for preparing the summit for him and
President Bush.
   ``Although we will be meeting on naval ships, I would like to
assure you that we will be speaking about peace, about how we can
work for a better world,'' he said.
</TEXT>
