<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1217EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Thailand-Guerrilla     12-02 0897</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Thailand-Guerrilla,0922</SECOND>
<HEAD>World's `Senior Surviving Guerrilla' Lays Down Arms</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENIS D. GRAY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chin Peng, one of the world's
longest-surviving and most secretive Communist guerrilla leaders,
laid down his arms Saturday after a half-century of jungle warfare.
   And the insurgency he started with the killing of three British
rubber planters 41 years ago in what is now Malaysia has formally
ended in a southern Thailand city known more for its sex trade than
politics.
   Now in his late 60s, Chin Peng signed an agreement ending the
armed struggle of the Communist Party of Malaya, which has within
its much-withered ranks some 1,200 weary jungle fighters who are to
return to civilian life.
   The Communists agreed to lay down their arms and pledged loyalty
to king and country. Thailand and Malaysia promised to ensure their
fair treatment.
   The signing ceremony at Hat Yai, a bustling center attracting
thousands of tourists and smuggled goods from nearby Malaysia,
marked another failure of communist effort around the world.
   Chin Peng called the agreements ``consistent with the current
historical trend where the peoples of the whole world are striving
for peace and democracy.''
   Chin Peng's future appears uncertain. Some Malaysian officials
have expressed suspicion of his motives, and the country appears
unwilling to accept ex-guerrillas once officially known as CTs, or
Communist Terrorists, who sought power through the barrel of a gun.
   Dubbed ``the world's senior surviving guerrilla'' by one Western
expert, Chin Peng belongs to a now all but vanished breed who
fought to create a Marxist-Leninist order following the chaos of
World War II.
   In World War II, the young Chin Peng was a courageous,
behind-enemy-lines fighter against the Japanese, learning guerrilla
tactics from his British comrades-at-arms in the jungles of Malaya,
formerly a British colony and now a part of Malaysia. He also
became a committed Communist.
   ``Unusual ability, an incisive brain, reliable, a frank man
(who) possessed marked courage, and commanded the natural respect
of men without fuss or formality,'' one of the British officers,
John Davis, said of him.
   He was awarded the Order of the British Empire after the war.
Soon, however, he became secretary-general of the Communist Party.
   He was born in 1920 or 1922 in Malaya's Perak State of Chinese
parents who immigrated to Malaya shortly before his birth. His
father made a good living selling and repairing bicycles and sent
his son to local English schools where he excelled.
   The Chinese were in many respects an underprivileged class in
British-ruled Malaya, and for a number of young people among them,
communism represented social justice and a shortcut to power and
status.
   In 1948 the party decided to wage armed struggle, the opening
volleys of which were fired June 16 when guerrillas walked into two
rubber plantations in northern Malaya and methodically executed
three planters.
   The country was plunged into 12 years of violence known as the
Malayan Emergency. It became one of the few successful efforts by a
government to stamp out a communist insurgency within its borders.
Later, in the Vietnam War, the U.S. government sought advice from
some of the architects of the victory, but conditions were far
different in America's war.
   At the height of the Emergency, some 70,000 British, Australian,
New Zealand, Fijian, Gurkha and other British Commonwealth troops
fought about 10,000 guerrillas. More than 10,000 fighters and
civilians died between 1948 and 1960.
   Although the casualties were relatively light, the jungle
fighting was agonizing and the communist attacks vicious. Tens of
thousands of often innocent Chinese were uprooted as a result of
the ultimately successful strategy to separate the guerrillas from
all sources of support.
   Clearly losing, Chin Peng emerged from the jungle in 1955 to
negotiate with Malayan officials at a schoolhouse near the
Thai-Malay border.
   Tunku Abdul Rahman, shortly to become prime minister of an
independent Malaysia, insisted on surrender and an amnesty. But
Chin Peng wanted his party included in a coalition government and
the talks broke down.
   ``The amnesty means surrender, surrender means humiliation. We
will not accept surrender at any time,'' Chin Peng said. ``If you
demand our surrender, we would prefer to fight to the last man.''
   Davis, his wartime friend, was present and the two men shook
hands before Chin Peng disappeared into the jungle. It was the last
time he was seen by the non-communist world until his recent
emergence in Thailand, which brokered the agreement.
   Although the Emergency was declared over in 1960, communist
attacks continued. Their last major raids were in the mid-1970s,
when guerrillas blew up the National War Memorial in Kuala Lumpur.
Thereafter, communist strength was sapped through joint
Thai-Malaysian military operations and a Thai amnesty that saw mass
surrenders in recent years.
   Chin Peng reportedly spent most of his time in China, making
periodic trips to the rugged Thai-Malaysian border where the
Malayan Communists were largely concentrated. There also were
reports of his death.
   Chin Peng became a legendary figure, the ruthlessness of his
movement mingling with the personal respect he had elicited from
his enemies.
   C.C. Too, the onetime Malaysian psychological warfare chief who
matched wits with him, described Chin Peng in a 1976 interview as
having ``a scholarly, monastic quality. When he talked and acted,
it was with dignity.
   ``If there is a Communist who can be called gentlemanly it was
Chin Peng,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891202-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1216EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r p AM-NewDemocrats     12-02 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-New Democrats,570</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Democratic Group Claims Inspiration from Hart, McCarthy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN L. HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fledgling faction of the Democratic Party is
organizing under the title ``New Democrats'' with plans to promote
liberal candidates in coming elections.
   The group claims the support of former presidential candidates
Eugene McCarthy and Gary Hart in its self-declared mission of
wresting control of the party from ``political managers,
technocrats and media consultants.''
   McCarthy, whose early success in the 1968 Democratic primaries
led President Lyndon B. Johnson to abandon his re-election bid, has
accepted the position of director of the New Democrats' steering
committee.
   He said he hopes the group can help counter the notion that
wearing a liberal tag is a political liability.
   Democrats, not the Republicans, must shoulder the blame for
liberalism's evolution into the dreaded ``L word'' of the last
presidential campaign, the former Minnesota senator said in an
interview.
   ``Gradually the word began to take on the characteristic of a
noun. At that point it was subject to all kinds of attacks by the
conservatives,'' McCarthy said.
   ``But then in the 80s, liberals began to attack liberalism and
admit that it had these serious faults. I think (New York Mayor Ed)
Koch said he was a sane liberal _ the implication being that all
other liberals were insane.''
   Hart, a former Colorado senator and frontrunner in the 1988
presidential campaign until a furor over his private life sabotaged
his standing, has given his blessing to the movement but declined a
leadership position, the New Democrats say.
   The group's founder, Jesse Yoder, is a philosophy professor at
the University of Lowell in Massachusetts who worked in McCarthy's
1968 campaign. He said the group plans to field its first
candidates for political office in 1990, including congressional
races.
   Philadelphia-area political activist and sports handicapper
Darcy Richardson said he intends in January to become the first
congressional candidate to run as a New Democrat.
   ``I think the New Democrats label will draw some attention.
It'll make people look twice and at least give us a hearing,'' said
Richardson, who has his eye set on Pennsylvania's 13th
congressional district seat currently held by Republican Lawrence
Coughlin.
   The New Democrats will try to unite the Woodstock generation
with the younger one politically weaned on Reaganomics, Yoder said.
   The group's positions include rolling back tax breaks for the
wealthy, immediate reductions in automotive and industrial
pollution levels, and higher pay for teachers.
   ``People who were around in '68 are now the decision makers
today and I think those are the people we will appeal to, but of
course we'll also be appealing to new people _ the students and
others within the party who see the merit of emphasizing the
envirnment, the economy and education,'' Yoder said.
   James Thurber, director of the Center for Congressional and
Presidential Studies at American University, is among the skeptics
who say the new group is unlikely to ever put a Democrat in the
White House.
   Any faction trying to rescue the Democratic Party should be
appealing to southern conservatives such as Sens. Charles Robb of
Virginia and Sam Nunn of Georgia, not liberals, he said.
   ``They will not be able to pull from the South. If you cannot
pull from the South, you lose the election,'' Thurber said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
