<FIRST>r i AM-MotherTeresa     12-02 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mother Teresa,0177</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Teresa Fine After Receiving Pacemaker</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CALCUTTA, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nobel laureate Mother Teresa was doing
fine Saturday and resting comfortably a day after a pacemaker was
implanted to restore normalcy in her heartbeats, hospital officials
said.
   There was no recurrence of the mild bout of fever she suffered
Friday.
   ``Mother Teresa is cheerful and her general condition is good,''
a statement issued by the Woodlands Nursing Home hospital said.
   The 79-year-old Roman Catholic nun, who suffered a heart attack
in September, was admitted Wednesday to Woodlands Nursing Home.
   Hundreds of nuns of Missionaries of Charity, the headquarters of
her worldwide charity that cares for the destitute and the dying on
six continents, prayed for her recovery Saturday.
   The Yugoslav-born nun founded the charity in October 1959 in an
abandoned hostel donated by the city of Calcutta. The order, which
was formally recognized by the Vatican in 1965, expanded and now
has 3,000 nuns working in 87 countries.
   Mother Teresa won the 1979 Nobel Peace Prize for her work.
