<FIRST>r w AM-BennettProfile     12-02 0558</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bennett Profile,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Ethics Counsel Known as Tough But Fair</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY MARGASAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Washington attorney Robert S. Bennett, who has
won acquittals for many white collar defendants, is known as a
tough but fair negotiator with a quick grasp of legal issues.
   The Senate may have had that reputation in mind when it chose
the 50-year-old Bennett to look into the case of five senators
under fire for their role in the $2 billion Lincoln Savings and
Loan controversy.
   Bennett, whose office overlooks Pennsylvania Avenue five blocks
from the White House, was chosen by the Senate Select Committee on
Ethics as its special counsel in the case of the so-called
``Keating Five.''
   He will provide legal advice on whether any or all of the five
senators violated the rules when they met with banking regulators
on behalf of wealthy campaign donor Charles H. Keating Jr. in 1987.
At the time, Keating's Lincoln Savings and Loan of Irvine, Calif.
was collapsing and its failure is now expected to cost taxpayers $2
billion.
   The brother of national drug policy coordinator William Bennett,
stocky, animated Bob Bennett is described by fellow lawyers as a
tough negotiator who can quickly grasp complex legal issues.
   ``If I were one of the senators and had done nothing wrong, I
wouldn't worry,'' said attorney E. Lawrence Barcella Jr. ``But if I
were one of the senators and had something to worry about, I'd be
scared to death.''
   Bennett's role is to advise the committee on whether to launch a
formal investigation of the five: Alan Cranston, D-Calif.; Donald
W. Riegle Jr., D-Mich.; John Glenn, D-Ohio; John McCain, R-Ariz.;
and Dennis DeConcini, D-Ariz.
   Keating had contributed some $1.3 million to the senators'
campaigns and political causes.
   Bennett's role could become even more powerful if the panel
proceeds with a full-scale investigation and invites him to remain.
   For Bennett, that would not be a first-time experience. He was
the panel's counsel in the Abscam bribery case against former Sen.
Harrison A. Williams Jr., D-N.J. Williams resigned in 1982.
   In his report, Bennett said the senator's behavior was
``illegal, corrupt and unethical.''
   William Bennett, four years younger than his brother, said,
``When Bob got you in a headlock, that was it _ you didn't get out.
The thing is concentration. His brain is like a radar screen. When
Bob sizes up the topic, nothing interferes.''
   The president's drug coordinator recalls that he once was
roughed up by a neighborhood bully when he was about five.
   ``Bob went to the kid's house and when the mother answered the
door, he was very polite,'' William Bennett said. ``But when the
boy came to the door, Bob said, `This is for hitting my brother. He
decked him in the doorway. That's classic Bob.''
   Bennett's whose 55-member law firm has one of the nation's
largest law practices representing white collar defendants.
   Current and former clients include former Navy Secretary John F.
Lehman Jr.; four defense contractors in the Pentagon bribery
scandal known as Operation Ill Wind and the Boeing Co.
   Joseph E. diGenova, the former U.S. attorney for the District of
Columbia, praised Bennett's appointment.
   ``He can look at something and smell it and know when
something's wrong,'' said DiGenova. ``He's the kind of guy who has
judgment. He knows when enough is enough.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
