<FIRST>b i BC-Summit 1stLd-Writethru   12-02 0385</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0572,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summit Sessions, Dinner, Called on Account of High Winds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: AMer will be filed in 15 minutes. This ends the BC series.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush, stranded by high
winds and choppy seas aboard an American naval cruiser, canceled
his second round of summit talks and a dinner Saturday with Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev, White House officials announced.
   The summit was to resume on Sunday.
   Putting a sunny spin on a rain splattered day, the White House
said, ``We feel this has been a very productive day in terms of the
five-hour meeting this morning.'' There was no immediate word from
the Soviet delegation.
   Bush and Gorbachev had held five hours of talks earlier in the
day before Bush returned to his ship to prepare for the second
round and the dinner, which originally was supposed to have been
aboard the president's command ship, the Belknap.
   Bush was unable to cross 500 yards of roiling waters to reach
Gorbachev, resting on a luxurious Soviet cruise liner tied up at
shore.
   A White House statement, making fun of the frustration, said,
``The 60 miles per hour winds preclude any movements off the ship
this evening, but they have made for a very exciting afternoon
sail.''
   Stranded on the Belknap along with Bush were Secretary of State
James A. Baker III, Brent Scowcroft, the president's national
security adviser, and Marlin Fitzwater, the president's press
secretary.
   The meeting on ships in the Mediterranean had been Bush's idea
for the beginning, but the White House tried to share any
embarrassment with the Soviets.
   ``We are disappointed that the Soviet delegation was unable to
join us for dinner on Belknap due to the storm,'' the statement
said, adding that U.S. officials look forward to Sunday's scheduled
meeting.
   ``We also regret that we were unable to visit the Slava for this
afternoon's meeting,'' it added. The Slava, a Soviet naval cruiser,
was to have been the site for Saturday's meeting, but the talks
were moved to a Soviet cruise liner docked at the shore.
   Stating the obvious, the statement said that Bush and his
delegation would remain on the Belknap for the night. ``We expect
Sunday's schedule to be maintained as orginally planned,'' it said.
</TEXT>
