<FIRST>u i AM-SummitRdp1stLd-Writethru a0580   12-02 0937</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit Rdp 1st Ld-Writethru, a0580,900</SECOND>
<HEAD>EDS: Inserts new grafs 3-4 with Soviet comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERENCE HUNT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP White House Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush and Soviet President
Mikhail S. Gorbachev, meeting at a storm-curtailed summit,
discussed the political upheaval in in Eastern Europe on Saturday
and vowed to respond to events with ``with sensitivity and firm
initiative,'' U.S. officials said.
   After five hours of talks that began with handshakes and smiles
between the two leaders, a White House statement said the meetings
``were marked by a spirit of forward-looking cooperation during
these increasingly changing times.''
   But gale-force winds and roiling seas forced cancellation of
afternoon talks and a scheduled dinner. Bush was unable to leave
the USS Belknap and cross 500 yards of Meditereanean Sea to reach
Gorbachev, resting on a luxurious Soviet cruise liner tied up at
shore.
   Both sides said the reason for the change in schedule was the
weather.
   Referring to the talks held before weather intervened, Gennady
Gerasimov, Gorbachev's spokesman, said ``things went well. They
talked about everything, arms, Europe, philosphical questions.''
   Bush opened the morning meeting with an hour-long presentation,
proposing more than a dozen ideas for economic and political
progress in U.S.-Soviet relations, the White House statement said,
without elaboration.
   It said the talks ranged from the economic situation in Eastern
Europe to arms control and Central America, and added that
Gorbachev spoke at length about perestroika, his program of
economic restructuring, and the goals of his reform program.
   State Department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler stressed there
was ``no other reason'' for the change in schedule except the
weather.
   A White House statement said, ``The 60 miles per hour winds
preclude any movements off the ship this evening, but they have
made for a very exciting afternoon sail.''
   Bush and Gorbachev had been scheduled to wrap up their talks on
Sunday, and the White House said ``we expect'' that to be the case.
   The weather aside, the White House assessment of the talks was
upbeat. ``We feel this has been a very productive day in terms of
the five hour meeting this morning,'' said the White House.
   ``I think we've got a very good beginning of the dialogue ... an
excellent beginning,'' Secretary of State James A. Baker III told
reporters after Bush and Gorbachev completed their initial session.
   ``They recognized that economic and political challenges were
ahead for Eastern Europe, and voewed to consider the opportunities
presented with sensitivity and firm initiative,'' said the
statement issued later.
   ``The first thing to do is eliminate those types of ships which
you cannot board in this kind of weather,'' Gorbachev joked to Bush
as he welcomed him aboard.
   ``We will have a secret agenda in this way to disarm the (U.S.)
Sixth Fleet,'' the Soviet leader said with a laugh. The Soviets are
serious, however, in pressing the United States to agree to
reductions in naval forces as part of arms control negotiations and
to remove nuclear weapons from the Mediterranean zone.
   As the small talk ended, Bush said, ``Let's go to work.''
   Bush braved the choppy seas in a small launch to get to the
Soviet liner, and then ran into trouble when he returned to his
command ship, the cruiser USS Belknap, also anchored about 500
yards from land.
   His launch had to make four passes at the Belknap before he
could board.
   The White House sought to minimize the effect the bad weather
was having on the summit and put an upbeat spin on the talks,
saying that Bush thought the talks were ``extremely productive.''
   Senior Soviet officials said Gorbachev wants the summit to
produce a timetable for completing U.S.-Soviet treaties on reducing
strategic nuclear weapons, conventional forces in central Europe
and chemical weapons.
   These officials, who spoke only on condition they not be
identified, said Gorbachev will convene a meeting of Warsaw Pact
leaders in Moscow on Monday to discuss the results of the two-day
summit. Bush will spend Monday briefing allied leaders at NATO
headquarters in Brussels, Belgium.
   Gorbachev and Bush were smiling and in high spirits as they
clasped hands across a long rectangular table, measuring barely a
yard across.
   ``It's so narrow that if we don't have enough arguments, we'll
kick each other,'' Gorbachev told Bush.
   Asked by reporters if they would reach make any achievements,
Gorbachev replied, `` da, da (yes, yes).'' On what? he was asked.
``Mnogovo,'' which was translated as meaning ``a lot of things.''
   When Bush was asked the same question, the president echoed
Gorbachev. ``Mnogovo,'' he said.
   The two leaders met in the plush surroundings of a library-like
room known as the Card Room, next to the ship's lounge and
nightclub, on the Maxim Gorky's promenade deck.
   They sat in deep captain's chairs, accompanied by aides on
either side.
   Bush, who had spent the night on the storm-buffeted Belknap,
said he had not been bothered by the rough weather. ``Piece of
cake,'' he said.
   Bush and Gorbachev held three rounds of talks that the White
House said amounted to almost continuous discussions between 10:05
a.m. until 3 p.m.
   They began with an expanded meeting that included at least 16
people and then held a one-on-one session, with notetakers, that
lasted about 1{ hours. That was followed by a working lunch, after
which Bush returned to the Belknap for some private time.
   The rain and wind disrupted Raisa Gorbachev's sightseeing plans.
She at first canceled plans to visit a 16th Century cathedral,
choosing to remain aboard the Gorky, but then later went ahead with
the tour. First lady Barbara Bush did not accompany Bush to the
Mediterranean.
</TEXT>
