<FIRST>r w AM-McLaughlinSuit     12-02 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-McLaughlin Suit,190</SECOND>
<HEAD>Talk Show Hosts Harassment Suit Reported Settled</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $4 million sexual harassment and
discrimination lawsuit filed against political talk show host John
J. McLaughlin by a former employee reportedly has been settled out
of court.
   Attorneys for McLaughlin and the woman who brought the suit,
Linda D. Dean, confirmed the settlement but refused to disclose the
terms, The Washington Post reported in its Saturday editions.
   Aides to McLaughlin and his attorney, Fred F. Fielding, said
Saturday afternoon they were not immediately available to confirm
the report.
   McLaughlin, 60, is host of ``The McLaughlin Group,'' a political
panel show that airs weekly on 230 public television stations and
four NBC-affiliated stations.
   The U.S. District Court lawsuit, filed in August 1988, described
a ``work environment which was hostile to women'' and charged
McLaughlin with ``sexually degrading and offensive remarks and
behavior ... toward past and present female employees.''
   Fielding issued a statement at the time the suit was filed
saying that McLaughlin and his production company ``emphatically
deny these bizarre and outrageous allegations.''
   McLaughlin, a former Jesuit priest and onetime speech writer for
Richard M. Nixon, has been married since 1975 to Ann Dore
McLaughlin, who was a secretary of Labor in the Reagan
administration.
