<FIRST>u i AM-Czechoslovakia 1stLd-Writethru a0581 12-02 0926</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0581,0949</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Disarms Communist Militia; Havel Urges Quick Reforms</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with army disarming Communist militia,
details; Picks up 2nd graf, `The beleaguered ...'; DELETES last 2 grafs
to tighten.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-East Bloc Notebook, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALISON SMALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The army began disarming the
Communist Party's paramilitary force on Saturday, putting thousands
of rifles into warehouses at the demand of opposition leaders.
   And Czechoslovakia's leading dissident warned the new coalition
government being formed this weekend to implement democratic
reforms without delay or face renewed opposition from millions who
have taken to the streets.
   The People's Militia, the force created 40 years ago to protect
the workplace from counterrevolution and later guarded the
Communists' monopoly on power, began surrendering weapons to the
army, the state-run news agency CTK reported. All weapons were
expected to be in army hands by Sunday.
   ``This is to honor a pledge by the new Communist leadership that
in the solution of the current political situation (the
paramilitary) means of the party will not be used,'' an unnamed
Politburo member was quoted as saying.
   The action came one day after Politburo member Vasil Mohorita
agreed to turn over control of the Communists' militia to the state
as a concession to opposition demands that the militia be disbanded.
   There was no mention of the future of the militia.
   The gray-uniformed militia is a paid, part-time force that is
believed to have tens of thousands of members recruited from among
workers. It was last used in January to help riot police smash a
weeklong series of demonstrations in Prague.
   In its terse dispatch, CTK noted that the Politburo spokesman
made the announcement after concerns were expressed by segments of
the population over ``increased movement of military vehicles on
Czechoslovak territory.''
   That was an obvious attempt to dispel any fears of army
intervention to reverse the democratic reforms that have been
promised.
   The beleaguered Communist-controlled government last week agreed
to appoint a new government by Sunday that will include
non-Communists for the first time since Warsaw Pact tanks crushed
``Prague Spring'' reforms in 1968.
   Playwright Vaclav Havel, a leader of the Civic Forum opposition
group, said the rapid pace of change must continue.
   ``If we are to structure our society in a democratic, peaceful,
decent and loving way, and avoid possible conflicts, then it is
necessary for the government to act quickly, and not only declare
certain things, but really implement them,'' he told the Communist
Party daily Rude Pravo.
   ``Any kind of postponement or delay would turn not only against
us, that is in this case the Civic Forum, but also against the
government and the entire society,'' Havel said.
   ``It would mean that all of us failed to manage the situation,''
he added.
   Havel spoke after six tough hours of negotiations Friday with
Czech Prime Minister Frantisek Pitra on the shape of the new
government.
   Federal Premier Ladislav Adamec agreed Tuesday in talks with
Havel and other Civic Forum representatives to include
non-Communists in the government. An announcement was expected
Sunday, government spokesman Marcel Jansen said.
   Because Czechoslovakia is a federation of the Czech and Slovak
republics, formation of the new federal government will have to be
accompanied by overhauls in the Czech and Slovak governments.
Justice and education, for instance, two key areas in which the
opposition seeks reforms, are controlled by the republic
governments.
   Civic Forum spokesman Jiri Dienstbier told The Associated Press
the opposition is not proposing specific candidates for the new
Cabinet but concentrating on outlining what characteristics the
office holders should have.
   Communists, members of previously docile allied parties, and
non-party people are acceptable to Civic Forum if they have no
obvious blemishes in their pasts and are willing to implement
reforms now that will lead to free elections and genuine democracy,
Dienstbier said.
   Civic Forum, established only 13 days ago, is an umbrella
movement of opposition groups. Its leaders have said they are not
offering themselves for Cabinet posts but have left open the
possibility of accepting nominations.
   ``I am a writer by profession, and I'd like to stay one,'' Havel
said, when asked by Rude Pravo if he aimed for office. ``I never
had ambitions of being a politician. I don't feel qualified for
it.''
   ``I'd like to get back into the theater,'' he said. Havel's
plays were banned for 20 years here until censorship was largely
removed last week.
   ``I firmly believe and hope that it will not be necessary (for
me to become a politician) and that the common good, which I always
place above my own interests, is not going to force me into
anything of the kind,'' Havel said.
   The formation of the new government will cap a week of historic
changes, brought on by 11 days of anti-government demonstrations
and a nationwide general strike Monday that sent millions into the
streets.
   On Tuesday, Adamec agreed to include non-Communists in the
government.
   On Wednesday, Parliament formally removed the Communists'
guaranteed leading role in politics from the constitution. A
Politburo member said free elections would be held within a year.
   On Friday, the Communists dramatically reversed 21 years of
policy, condemning the 1968 invasion that crushed the ``Prague
Spring'' reforms, and paving the way for a formal reassessment by
the Warsaw Pact in Moscow later this month.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev swiftly followed the
admission by saying the 1968 reforms were correct and democratic
and that the Soviet-led invasion was an ``inappropriate response''
from Moscow.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891202-0091 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1501EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-BestLaidPlans 1stLd-Writethru a0570 12-02 0750</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Best Laid Plans, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0570,770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Marooning of Bush Forces Interruption of Summit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: Updates to reflect summit changes. Editing throughout. ^By
JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   George Bush, commander-in-chief of
the world's largest Navy, was marooned on his own ship Saturday as
a fierce December gale bewildered the best-laid plans of superpower
leaders, protesters and local tourism officials.
   ``This is the type of weather that shipwrecked Saint Paul on
these rocks. We usually have this in February,'' said Joe Cassar, a
government official on Malta, host country to the snake-bit
superpower summit.
   Winds gusting to 60 miles per hour and thundering foam-topped
waves forced a postponement of a second round of talks between Bush
and Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev until Sunday, as well as
cancellation of a scheduled dinner.
   The weather also played havoc at the fringes of the summit. A
big anti-nuclear parade was postponed until Sunday and Raisa
Gorbachev's schedule of sightseeing on the island was disrupted.
   This wasn't what local tourism officials had in mind, either. A
government travel brochure describes Malta as the ``perfect winter
holiday destination.''
   ``The sun worshipper who flees Northern Europe's cold and damp
winter weather finds in Malta the perfect refuge,'' the brochure
says, adding that the island 's mild winter climate ``makes it
possible to practice quite a variety of winter sports.''
   Be that as it may, seas that built overnight forced a change of
sites for the opening session between Bush and Gorbachev.
   Instead of holding the morning meeting aboard the Soviet cruiser
Slava, the leaders met aboard a Soviet luxury liner docked at a
pier in a more sheltered part of the bay. The liner, the Maxim
Gorky, normally caters to West German tourists on North Sea cruises.
   Bush crossed the choppy bay from his summit headquarters aboard
the USS Belknap to the Gorky without incident on a canopy-covered
admiral's barge. But returning after lunch was more of a problem as
the heaving launch had to make three passes before it could safely
deliver Bush to the U.S. ship.
   Then, the weather got worse. Bush, a former naval aviator and
speedboat enthusiast, wound up stuck on the cruiser for the night.
   ``The 60 mile per hour winds preclude any movements off the ship
this evening, but they have made for a very exciting afternoon
sail,'' said a statement by White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater.
   Fitzwater was stranded with Bush, as were Secretary of State
James A. Baker III and National Security Adviser Brent Scowcroft.
   ``They cannot get off of the Belknap,'' said Baker's aide,
Margaret Tutwiler.
   Sig Rogich, director of advance planning for the White House,
was asked if he was disappointed that the elaborately staged scene
of the ships and meetings had been disrupted by the weather. Rogich
frowned slightly and nodded.
   The original script called for Bush to travel by boat from the
8,600-ton Belknap to the 12,500-ton Slava to begin his talks with
Gorbachev.
   Conditions were not bad enough as to endanger anyone on board
the heavy warships, but the waves were rough enough to make getting
on and off from smaller shuttle craft a major problem.
   Summit planners apparently considered moving Saturday's meeting
to land, but finally decided to use the 25,000-ton Gorky,
Gorbachev's floating residence during the weekend. It is moored at
a pier about 1,000 yards from the Belknap.
   Moving the talks to the Gorky in case of bad weather was one of
several contingencies that had been discussed prior to the weekend,
said the assistant to the Maltese prime minister who has been in
charge of planning the Maltese side of the meeting.
   ``It is December in the Mediterranean,'' said Richard Cacchia
Caruana, noting the weather is always undependable this time of
year. ``We made sure that both the Soviets and the Americans knew
about it.''
   ``We've done the best we could in three weeks,'' said Cacchia
Caruana philosophically. ``We really couldn't do anything about the
weather.''
   Fear of bad weather was one reason it was decided to hold the
summit in Marsaxlokk Bay rather than further off the coast of
Malta, he said.
   Cold air from western Russia appeared to be the culprit for the
low pressure system causing the strong easterly winds over the
central Mediterranean, said Maltese meteorologist Spiro Agius.
   ``It will definitely be improving tomorrow,'' Agius added.
   But maybe not.
   Forecaster David Membrey of the London Weather Center said to
expect the strong winds to continue through Sunday afternoon.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
