<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1403EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Lebanon     12-02 0655</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon,0680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bomb Tossed at Cabinet Minister's Home; No Injuries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb was tossed from a speeding car
Saturday at the south Lebanon home of Information Minister Edmond
Rizk, a foe of Christian Gen. Michel Aoun, causing damage but no
injuries, police said.
   Also Saturday, Aoun's command accused Syrian forces of firing at
a Lebanese army helicopter hovering over thousands of Aoun
supporters forming a human wall around his headquarters in the
presidential palace.
   A communique said eight supporters were wounded by falling
shrapnel from a Syrian anti-aircraft barrage, which missed the
helicopter.
   ``Gen. Aoun bestowed military medals on the eight injured
youths,'' the communique said. It did not specify the seriousness
of their injuries.
   The Syrian army command in Lebanon did not comment.
   The incident occurred a few hours before the arrival of eight
French lawmakers to declare support for Aoun, who opposes Lebanon's
Syrian-backed president and has vowed to drive Syrian troops out of
Lebanon.
   Rizk, a Maronite like Aoun, was in Moslem west Beirut when his
house was bombed at 10:30 a.m. in his hometown of Jizzine, 25 miles
south of the capital.
   His wife and children, who were at the house, escaped injury,
according to police.
   Rizk was among the Lebanese legislators who approved an
Arab-brokered peace plan for Lebanon in a special Parliament
session in Taif, Saudi Arabia in October. Aoun opposed the accord
because it does not set a timetable for the withdrawal of the
40,000 Syrian troops in Lebanon.
   The accord cleared the way for election of a president.
   Rizk was named information minister in Lebanon's newly formed
national reconciliation government, which was entrusted with
applying the Taif accord to end 14 years of civil war.
   Rizk's house was the first to be attacked in areas controlled by
the South Lebanon Army, a predmoninantly Christian militia allied
with Israel.
   There were similar bomb attacks on the homes of eight other
legislators in the Christian enclave controlled by Aoun's army in
the past five weeks.
   Rizk blamed the attack on ``Gen. Aoun and agents he recruited to
undermine the whole of Lebanon.''
   The right-wing French parliamentarians did not make any
statements when they arrived at the shell-wrecked presidential
palace in Baabda, five miles east of Beirut.
   They held a brief meeting with Aoun, who refuses to give up the
palace to President Elias Hrawi. Hrawi was elected by Parliament
last month after Rene Mouawad was assassinated by a bomb after 17
days in office.
   The French legislators then joined a dance with some of the
thousands of Christian youths camped in the woods around the palace
since Tuesday to raise the ante if Syria decides to attack Aoun.
   Last week, 33 right-wing French Parliament members visited the
Christian enclave for 24 hours to declare support for Aoun.
   The Moslem Voice of the Nation radio said the final decision on
how to evict Aoun from the palace will be taken this week.
   It said Hrawi agreed to delay the move in an effort to prevent
bloodshed.
   ``But if Aoun refuses to end his mutiny peacefully, then the
proper decision will be taken,'' the radio said.
   An-Nahar, an independent daily, quoted Hrawi as saying an
assault to dislodge Aoun has been delayed at the request of a
``number of Arab and foreign states'' that he did not identify.
   But at a news conference Thursday, Hrawi said, ``The day of
judgment is very near.'' Hrawi, a Maronite Christian like Aoun,
stressed that he hoped Aoun would leave the palace peacefully.
   Hrawi's remark coincided with a buildup of Syrian tanks,
artillery, and commando forces around the 310-square-mile Christian
enclave north of Beirut, an apparent preparation for an assault to
dislodge Aoun.
   Syrian troops were deployed in Lebanon in 1976 under an Arab
League peacekeeping mandate to quell the civil war fighting. Aoun
said they abrogated the mandate by siding with the Moslems.
</TEXT>
