<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1426EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Bulgaria     12-02 0298</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Bulgaria,0307</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bulgarian Leadership Condemns 1968 Invasion of Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New reform-minded Communist Party leaders
have condemned the 1968 Warsaw Pact invasion of Czechoslovakia in
which Bulgarian troops took part, the state-run news agency BTA
said Saturday.
   Each of the five Warsaw Pact nations that joined in the invasion
of their neighbor has recently criticized the operation. Soviet
President Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Friday called the invasion an
``inappropriate response.''
   The ruling party Politburo and the government studied the issue
and noted that the decision to crush Czechoslovakia's ``Prague
Spring'' reforms was conditioned by the international situation at
the end of the 1960s, BTA said.
   BTA said that situation was ``characterized by confrontation,
armament races and relentless ideological fighting.'' The Warsaw
Pact decision to send tanks and troops was influenced by ``deformed
concepts of socialist society.
   ``Looking back from today's point of view,'' BTA said, ``and
from the positions of restructuring and new political thinking, the
action taken in August 1968 is assessed as unjustifiable and
illegal.
   ``History has proved it to be wrong and incompatible with the
new course of the Bulgarian Communist Party and the Bulgarian
state,'' said BTA, which reflects government policy.
   Referring to the moves toward democratization in Czechoslovakia,
BTA said ``the dynamic processes which have been recently triggered
in Czechoslovakia are received in Bulgaria with understanding and
sympathy.''
   Led by the Soviet Union, every Warsaw Pact nation except Romania
took part in the 1968 invasion, which crushed democratic reforms
and led to the installation of hard-line Communist leaders.
   The invasion recently has been condemned by leaders of Hungary,
Poland and East Germany, as well as Czechoslovakia.
   Bulgaria's longtime hard-line Communist Party chief Todor
Zhivkov was ousted on Nov. 10 and replaced by Petar Mladenov, who
is considered more moderate.
</TEXT>
