<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1441EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Yugoslavia     12-02 0370</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Yugoslavia,0386</SECOND>
<HEAD>Yugoslavian Leader Predicts Multiparty Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A member of Yugoslavia's collective
presidency said multiparty democracy is bound to prevail in this
Communist-ruled nation, a Zagreb daily reported Saturday.
   Stipe Suvar, the Croatian republic's representative in the
eight-person Yugoslav presidency, was quoted as saying Communism
``is heading for the reconstruction of political (freedoms) that
will certainly result in a multiparty system.''
   His comments were in an interview carried in the Vjesnik daily
newspaper.
   ``I would prefer for two parties to emerge ... and to creatively
compete,'' he was quoted as saying, adding that ``even if the
present Communist Party were to disintegrate, a new party would
eventually emerge in its ashes.''
   He also blasted the republic of Serbia for severing ties with
the more liberal republic of Slovenia, the newspaper reported.
   Mass Serbian rallies ``cannot make Yugoslavia a happier place,''
he was quoted as saying.
   In an unprecedented move, the leadership of Serbia, Yugoslavia's
largest republic, broke off all business and government contacts
with Slovenia Wednesday after authorities there banned the rally by
an estimated 40,000 Serbs. They were reportedly seeking the ouster
of Slovenia's liberal leadership.
   Yugoslavia consists of six republics and two autonomous
provinces, each with its own government and party structure.
   The decentralized system of government and a collective federal
presidency were devised to prevent one republic from gaining sway
over the others, but it has often resulted in tensions and
ineffective government by compromise.
   In the interview, Suvar also described the current
counterrevolutionary activities trial of Azem Vlasi, a former
leader of hard-line Serbia's southern province of Kosovo, as
``unnecessary and harmful'' for Yugoslavia. He called for Vlasi's
release.
   In Yugoslavia's largest political trial in decades, Vlasi and 14
other ethnic Albanian defendants are accused of opposing Serbia in
its drive to strengthen its control over the impoverished province.
   Kosovo has been the scene of continuing unrest that left at
least 28 people dead this year.
   Ethnic Albanians, who make up almost nine-tenths of the region's
1.9 million people, are seeking greater autonomy for their
province. Serbia exercises some control over Kosovo, though it is
nominally autonomous.
   Vlasi's trial has been sharply criticized in Slovenia and by
international human rights groups.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
