<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1444EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Israel 1stLd-Writethru   12-02 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0566,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Conducts Major Anti-Guerrilla Sweep in West Bank</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Leads with 10 grafs to restore attribution in 3rd graf, UPDATE
with Palestinian death. Pickup 10th pvs, `Mordechai spoke...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NABLUS, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hundreds of Israeli troops
seized uniforms, hatchets and homemade swords on Saturday during
house-to-house searches in an area where the army had killed four
armed Palestinians.
   At least 30 Arabs were detained during the operation, which came
one day after soldiers clashed with seven members of a Palestinian
gang called the Black Panthers outside a barber shop in the Casbah
quarter of Nablus. Four Palestinians were slain during the clash.
   In the Gaza Strip on Saturday, Israeli soldiers shot and wounded
23 Palestinians during a sympathy strike for the four, Arab reports
said.
   Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai on Saturday blamed the Black
Panthers for killing 16 Palestinians suspected of collaborating
with Israel and said its activities were directed by Yasser
Arafat's Fatah faction of the PLO.
   Since the start of the Palestinian uprising, underground groups
known as ``strike forces'' and ``popular committees'' have been
formed to enforce orders of its PLO-backed leadership. Some of
these groups have gradually focused on violent interrogations and
killings of suspected collaborators as a main activity.
   In the past four months of his command, Mordechai said 130
hard-core activists had been arrested from groups such as the Black
Panthers and Red Eagles, which have used weapons in attacks on
Israeli soldiers and killed Palestinians suspected of having ties
to Israeli authorities.
   The use of weapons contradicts PLO policy against using arms in
the nearly 2-year-old Palestinian uprising.
   Recent leaflets from the pro-PLO underground criticized the
slaying of alleged collaborators and disowned the renegade actions
of unauthorized groups.
   Some 154 Palestinians have been killed by other Arabs, while 624
Palestinians have been killed by Israelis during the uprising.
   The latest death came Saturday when Hamad Jaber, 20, of the West
Bank village of Tayasir, died of wounds suffered in a clash with
troops three weeks ago.
   Mordechai spoke at the site of Friday's shootout outside Kamal's
Salon, a barber shop in the Casbah quarter, where 30,000
Palestinians live.
   Bloodstains, broken window panes and shards of porcelain coffee
cup were seen. An army officer said slain Black Panther leader Imad
Nasser, 29, was holding the cup when soldiers approached the group.
   Across the street, two Palestinian men in their 20s kneeled
against a graffiti-covered wall, hands bound behind their backs and
blindfolded.
   Army officers said more than 30 Palestinians were detained
Saturday. Unofficial reports estimated the number of detainees at
60 to 100.
   ``I think the people of Nablus will be be grateful to hear that
this group is under control,'' said Mordechai, who claimed to have
documents linking the Black Panthers to senior Fatah officials.
``Behind this group are high-level PLO officials supporting, giving
money and encouraging them.''
   ``There is no serious group left operating in this area,'' said
Col. Raanan Gissin, deputy army spokesman who guided reporters on a
tour of the Casbah, where a curfew kept residents off the streets.
   Reporters were taken to a secondary school where soldiers had
collected dozens of knives and swords, piles of uniforms, outlawed
PLO flags, slingshots, posters of Arafat, wooden clubs and axes.
   According to witness accounts from Arab reporters, Israeli
forces disguised as Arabs and wearing Arab headdresses arrived
Friday in a red Mercedes with distinctive blue West Bank license
plates. They surprised the Black Panthers in the barber shop and
opened fire.
   Mordechai described that account as a ``tall story.'' He said
the soldiers were in uniform and arrived on foot after being
alerted by an army lookout.
   Gissin said two Palestinians were killed on the spot and two
died of wounds later. He said one of those killed tried to grab the
gun of an Israeli soldier. Bloodstains mark the spot where he died.
   Drops of blood were also visible where three Black Panthers were
wounded.
   ``In these kind of clashes, you have to fire first if you want
to survive,'' Gissin said. ``The soldiers had no choice but to draw
fast and fire first.''
   Mordechai said the Palestnians did not get off a shot, but other
officers said one Palestinian weapon had a bullet in the chamber,
ready to fire.
</TEXT>
