<DOCNO> AP891202-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1506EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BollesCase 1stLd-Writethru a0559 12-02 0758</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bolles Case, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0559,0776</SECOND>
<HEAD>13 Years Later, New Probe Launched in Reporter's Death</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to CORRECT referenct to husband to ex-husband;
recasts 18th graf, `And some...' to CLARIFY jealousy theory.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY18</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY LOPEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 13 years after a car bomb killed an
investigative reporter for Arizona's largest newspaper, the murder
case has been reopened even though the motive is as murky as ever.
   When Attorney General Bob Corbin leans back and puts his cowboy
boots on the desk in his Old West-style office, he can choose from
a tangle of theories about who ordered the death of Arizona
Republic reporter Don Bolles.
   There's the mob. Casinos. Race track owners. Bankers. Even a
jealous ex-husband. And there are plots within plots. One theory is
that the hit men collected twice, from different people. So far,
though, only one man has been convicted, and the masterminds,
whoever they were, remain free.
   Corbin, a Republican whose office comes up for election next
year, has been attacked by potential challengers for not solving
the case. But he insists those attacks were not a factor in his
decision to reinstate a murder charge last week against James
Robison, a plumber accused of setting off the bomb.
   Corbin says he has ``new evidence'' but won't say what it is or
where it points.
   ``You don't need motive for a conviction,'' he said. ``It helps
... but I don't need to show motive.''
   Bolles, 47, died 11 days after the radio-controlled bomb blew up
his car in a hotel parking lot in June 1976. As he lay dying, he
was heard to say ``John Adamson,'' ``Emprise'' and ``Mafia.''
   Emprise Corp., now known as Delaware North Companies Ltd., was a
partner with the Funk family of Arizona in dog-racing tracks.
   John Harvey Adamson, 45, who ultimately became the only man
convicted in the case so far, was a greyhound breeder and tow-truck
operator who drank heavily and used cocaine. Bolles had left a note
at his desk saying he was planning to meet him to discuss a
land-fraud scheme involving high-level politicians.
   At trial, Adamson testified in return for leniency, saying he
planted the car bomb and Robison triggered it on orders from Max
Dunlap, a man trying to ingratiate himself with land and liquor
magnate Kemper Marley.
   Marley, a target of Bolles' stories, was never charged with the
crime, however, and an appeals court threw out the Robison and
Dunlap convictions. Dunlap was released, though Robison, 67,
remains in prison on an unrelated assault conviction.
   Corbin decided to drop charges against Robison and Dunlap when
Adamson refused to testify in a retrial unless he got a better deal
than he originally bargained for. Corbin, arguing that Adamson had
broken the plea bargain, brought him to trial and won a murder
conviction and death sentence he hoped would persuade Adamson to
talk.
   A federal appeals court threw out Adamson's death sentence
earlier this year, however, and Corbin filed a new murder charge
against Robison last week without waiting for further appeals to be
heard by the Supreme Court. A preliminary hearing is scheduled for
January.
   Separately, a state grand jury is investigating potential
obstruction of justice charges and has called in witnesses that
could fit several of the scenarios.
   Several people, including free-lance reporter Don Devereux, have
theorized that Bolles may have been killed because he was
investigating industrial gold thefts and their ties to California
bankers.
   Devereux and others have suggested Bolles was looking at
dog-track skimming, however, and they cite his dying words.
   Still others have linked the death to a ``Mafia diary'' that
describes casino skimming, but that some contend is a forgery.
   And some, including Corbin at one time, have pointed to a member
of the Funk family as a ``contingency suspect,'' saying he resented
his ex-wife's closeness with Bolles, whom she confided in.
   Some of the theories overlap, and there are those who believe
the hit men may have been paid originally by one person before
persuading a second who didn't know about the first contract to pay
for it too.
   Adamson declined to be interviewed last week, and Robison
referred a reporter to his attorney, who did not return calls.
   The reopening of the case pleased those close to Bolles.
   His brother Richard, an author, said: ``I'd just like to know
the truth.''
   John Winters, a Bolles colleague who still covers the case,
said: ``You at least have some activity going on in the case.''
</TEXT>
