<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-Olympics     12-02 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Olympics,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<UNK>Bush Asks Soviets To Join In Backing 2004 Olympic Bid for Berlin</UNK>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush urged Soviet leader
Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Saturday to join the United States in
proposing that the 2004 Olympics be held in Berlin, a U.S. official
said.
   The official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said the
Olympic proposal was among the subjects Bush raised on the first
day of his summit talks with Gorbachev. The discussions were
scheduled for a Soviet missile cruiser, but moved to the Soviet
liner Maxim Gorky because of bad weather.
   Berlin as a site for the Olympics was suggested by
then-President Ronald Reagan, at a time when the Berlin Wall _
symbol of Europe's division _ seemed to rule out any possibility.
Reagan did not propose a date.
   The idea of bidding for the 2004 games surged in Germany
immediately after the East Berlin government's decision Nov. 9 to
ease travel restrictions on its citizens and to cut new crossings
in the wall, allowing millions of East Germans to visit West Berlin
freely.
   Four West German cities preparing to bid for the 2004 summer
Olympics immediately said they would drop their applications if
Berlin were to become a candidate.
</TEXT>
