<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1529EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Taiwan-Voters     12-02 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Taiwan-Voters,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Taiwan Voters Given A Choice, Ask Gods For Advice</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Taiwan, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At the Sea Goddess Temple on Saturday, Li
Ying-shi tossed the wood blocks once, twice, three times.
   ``That's it,'' said the grizzled fisherman. ``Sea Goddess says
no voting today.''
   As he hobbled away, a young woman in a blue dress took his place
in front of the altar, facing an image of the fetching goddess.
   ``I've never voted before,'' she said with a shy smile after
tossing the blocks, a Buddhist ritual. ``I needed advice.''
   Indeed, for the first time in Taiwan's history, a legal
opposition party has given voters something close to real choice in
the first nationwide elections since martial law was lifted in 1987.
   Long lines formed at polling booths throughout the island.
   ``We've been going full steam since 8 a.m.,'' said one police
officer at a polling station near the Sea Goddess Temple in
northern Taipei. ``It's just getting busier.''
   As he spoke, three elderly women moved slowly out of the voting
booth.
   ``We choose the opposition,'' said one, as she stood between her
two sisters clutching their hands. ``We talked about it last night
and decided to vote our mind. The people must speak.''
   The opposition, or Democratic Progressive Party, ran a spirited
campaign against the ruling Nationalist Party, which has governed
Taiwan since 1949 when it fled mainland China after losing a civil
war to the Communists.
   The DPP finds its strength mostly among the Taiwanese working
class who were here when the mainlanders came over from China.
   The opposition portrayed the Nationalists as corrupt, accusing
them of vote-buying and using state-run television to push
Nationalist candidates.
   The Nationalists depicted the opposition as a chaotic band of
radicals, ready to proclaim Taiwan's cultural and political
independence from China.
   The issue was an emotional one because China has warned it could
attack Taiwan if this island of 20 million proclaims independence.
It also cut to the heart of the Nationalists claim on power. Ever
since fleeing to Taiwan, the Nationalists have said they alone are
the legitimate government of China.
   Hugh G. Chang, an 83-year-old retired Ministry of Finance
official, fled to Taiwan in 1948 to help set up a government for
the beleagured Nationalists and their leader Generalissimo Chiang
Kai-shek.
   After years of supporting Chiang's martial law policies, Chang
said he now he supports political liberalization.
   ``But slowly, slowly,'' he said, banging his cane on the
pavement. His grandson, Chang Yin-lien agreed.
   ``Instability is a bad thing,'' said the 25-year-old law student
who voted for the Nationalists with his grandfather in western
Taipei. ``We want calm for Taiwan.''
   Their viewpoint is common among Taiwan's people, strongly
influenced by Confucian ethics that worship harmony.
   Still, some voters said they didn't agree.
   ``A little turmoil may not be a bad thing,'' said one voter
after casting his ballot for the opposition. ``It's like marriage.
If you don't argue, you never make up.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891202-0109 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1531EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-LiverTransplant     12-02 0510</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Liver Transplant,0525</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alyssa's Condition Improving, Second Girl Awaits Surgery</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENDA C. COLEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 21-month-old girl was drinking liquids, growing
more alert and doing well Saturday, five days after becoming the
nation's first living-donor liver-transplant recipient, a hospital
spokesman said.
   While Alyssa Smith recovered with her mother, who gave the child
part of her liver Monday, surgeons at the University of Chicago
Medical Center were deciding whether a 15-month-old Tennessee girl
could undergo a similar operation.
   ``Doctors will continue to evaluate and assess the options and
decide whether she still fits the protocol for a living-donor''
liver transplant, said spokesman John Easton.
   Sarina Jones of Millington, Tenn., remained in serious condition
in the hospital's intensive care unit, a day after she was flown in
by air ambulance and taken by helicopter to the hospital, Easton
said.
   Sarina suffered from an infection recently, and was not
considered an immediate candidate for surgery.
   ``It doesn't look like it's going to be this weekend,'' said
medical center spokeswoman Mary Fetsch. ``It's tentatively set for
Wednesday.''
   Sarina's parents, Robert, 20, and Michelle, 21, who live near
Memphis, arrived Friday night, a few hours after their daughter.
   ``They said our chances were small, but they're still chances,''
said the father, a dry-wall installer and contractor.
   He is expected to act as donor for his blond, blue-eyed
daughter, who became a transplant candidate almost a year ago but
whose parents became frustrated waiting for a suitable organ in the
Memphis area.
   Both little girls suffered from biliary atresia, a usually fatal
genetic disorder involved in more liver transplants than other
ailments.
   Sarina's condition was more advanced than Alyssa's, however,
even though Alyssa had also waited a year after becoming a
transplant candidate, Ms. Fetsch said Friday.
   Alyssa's mother, 29-year-old schoolteacher Teresa Smith, was in
good condition Saturday while recuperating from the operation, in
which she donated the left lobe of her liver, Easton said.
   ``Mom's doing well,'' Easton said. ``I imagine she's still in
some discomfort. But she's not having any complications.''
   The girl's father, John L. Smith, 27, an assistant shipping
supervisor, has been at the hospital this week with his wife and
daughter, as well as the couple's 3-year-old son, Richard.
   The Smiths, of Schertz, Texas, near San Antonio, are the first
people to participate in a living-donor transplant in the United
States, which followed a total of four such procedures in other
countries _ Brazil, Australia and Japan. One child has died.
   The University of Chicago developed its living-donor
liver-transplant program, in which it hopes to perform the surgery
on 20 patients within 12 months, partly as a response to the
shortage of available organs from children's cadavers for
youngsters who need liver transplants. An estimated 25 to 50
percent of children who need liver transplants die without them.
   Dr. Christoph Broelsch, who led the surgical team in Monday's
operation on Alyssa, pioneered the technique of transplanting part
of adult organs into youngsters, whose abdominal cavities are too
small to hold a whole adult liver.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
