<DOCNO> AP891202-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1601EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-RiotTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0568 12-02 0879</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Riot Trial, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0568,0896</SECOND>
<HEAD>Miami Optimistic Riots Can Be Avoided _ But Ready _ As Trial Nears
End</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Barring last-minute ...' to ADD trial recessed
until Monday. SUBS 16th graf, ```Since 1919 ... ' with two grafs to CLARIFY
background of prior riots. Note language in 16th graf. Picks up 17th graf,
pvs, ```All these...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The memory of four previous riots this decade hangs
over Miami as the racially charged manslaughter trial of a
policeman nears its end, but this time there is hope the bloodshed
can be avoided.
   ``I've got a very good feeling about it,'' Miami's Mayor Xavier
Suarez said Friday after a visit to an school in a predominantly
black neighborhood. ``I think a couple of blacks on the jury _
that's very helpful. The process is going to be viewed this time as
complex, but fair.''
   Barring last-minute delays, the case of officer William Lozano,
31, accused of manslaughter in the deaths of a black motorcyclist
and his passenger, is expected to go to the six-member jury later
this week. The trial was recessed on Friday until Monday.
   Lozano faces two counts of manslaughter in the deaths of Clement
Lloyd, 23, and Lloyd's passenger, Allan Blanchard, 24. Lozano shot
Lloyd in the head, killing him instantly. Blanchard, also black,
died the next day of head injuries suffered in the subsequent crash.
   Four times since 1980 _ including the Jan. 16 shooting that led
to the current trial _ racial disturbances were touched off by
violent encounters between police and blacks, or by the subsequent
acquittal of the officers by all-white juries.
   Willie Sims, a black member of Dade County's Community Relations
Board, says he has felt the difference participation in the legal
system makes in the community's reaction.
   ``You have blacks on the jury, you have a black prosecutor,''
says Sims. ``It definitely goes a long way toward defusing the
situation _ you reduce the perception of unfairness.''
   Another difference is that the local media have given almost
blanket coverage of the trial. The school district's television
station WLRN runs a complete tape of the day's proceedings each
night. Radio station WINZ-AM interrupts its programming with live
broadcasts from the trial. Several commercial television
broadcasters _ including Cable News Network nationally _ carried
Lozano's appearance live on Thursday.
   The media have acted more responsibly than before the previous
riots, asserts Marvin Dunn, a prominent black sociologist and
author of a book on the May 1980 riot that left 18 people dead.
That violence followed the acquittal of policemen accused of
beating to death black insurance executive Arthur McDuffie.
   ``I just don't have a sense of any tremendous support for a riot
in the wake of an acquittal,'' Dunn says. ``In going around the
community, you don't hear the same level of anger as before the
McDuffie riot. ... There is an overwhelming sentiment in the
community for peace.''
   Another difference is that unlike 1980, the city police are
ready this time if there is unrest.
   The department has 700 new gas masks and two armored vehicles,
and has upgraded shields, batons and other equipment, says police
spokesman David Rivero. Police will move in quickly at the first
sign of trouble.
   ``We have a major plan where every policeman in this entire
department has an assignment,'' Rivero says. ``We are going to put
everybody in jail who breaks the law.''
   But not everyone shares the optimism of local officials, or
feels that two black jurors will be enough to prevent violence in
case of an acquittal.
   At the Nu Lounge _ a bar only 100 feet or so from where Lozano
shot Lloyd _ many patrons fear the trial will end in a replay of
what they see as a long history of injustice.
   ``Since 1919 until today, it's been the same _ `Get the
nigger,''' says Joseph Williams, 72, a lifelong resident of the
community. He mentions the McDuffie case and the 1982 shooting of
Nevell Johnson, a black, in a video arcade only a few blocks away,
which both sparked rioting.
   In 1984, violence broke out again when an all-white jury
acquitted Miami police officer Luis Alvarez in Johnson's shooting.
   ``All these things make the guy in the street feel like `a
policeman can kill me because I'm black,''' says Ivory Lewis, a
former policeman and now a longshoreman. ``That's why people want a
guilty verdict, so they feel our children's lives are worth
something.''
   While attention has focused on black neighborhoods where the
riots took place, the case also has riveted the attention of south
Florida's Hispanic community _ especially the 200,000 Colombians
who constitute the region's second-largest Latin ethnic group,
after Cuban-Americans.
   Even in Lozano's homeland of Colombia, news of the trial is
carried in detail by the media, and a fund-raising drive has helped
pay the expenses of his legal defense.
   Support for the policeman is widespread, says Dario Restrepo, a
member of Florida's official Commission on Hispanic Affairs and
governor of the Colombian American Chamber of Commerce.
   Lozano's brothers and his wife are all law enforcement officers,
he notes _ a welcome relief to a nationality whose country has
become synonymous with cocaine trafficking.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP891202-0111 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1553EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-US 1stLd-Writethru   12-02 0824</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-US, 1st Ld-Writethru,820</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Offers New Arms-Control, Trade Proposals, U.S. Officials Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: Combines material in a0628-a0629; 6th graf SUBS for 8th graf
pvs, On the negative xxx etc., to CORRECT to El Salvador, sted Nicaragua;
Editing changes thruout; No Pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush proposed to Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev on Saturday that NATO and the Warsaw
Pact conclude a treaty to reduce conventional forces in Europe next
year and sign the accord at an international summit meeting in
Vienna, U.S. officials said.
   The proposal was part of a presentation on arms control, trade,
human rights and other U.S.-Soviet issues that Bush outlined at the
opening round of talks with Gorbachev at their storm-tossed summit,
according to officials who asked not to be identified by name.
   Bush also suggested that Secretary of State James A. Baker III
and Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze meet next month
in the Soviet Union to resolve several key issues blocking
agreement on a separate treaty to reduce U.S. and Soviet long-range
nuclear weapons by 30 to 50 percent, the officials said.
   That pact would be signed at a superpower summit to be held in
the United States, which Bush suggested be held in the second half
of June, according to officials.
   The recommendations extended to a call for the two summit
partners to jointly propose Berlin as the site for the Olympic
Games in 2004 _ a gesture that would dramatize the improvement in
East-West relations.
   On the negative side, Bush told Gorbachev the continued delivery
of Soviet arms to leftist rebels in El Salvador through surrogates
was the single most destructive factor in the superpower
relationship, said the officials.
   The U.S. officials said Gorbachev did not respond directly to
any of Bush's initiatives. Presumably, the response, at least in
part, would come on Sunday during a final day of talks.
   On the arms-control front, officials said that Bush was willing
to end production of U.S. chemical weapons once an international
treaty is put into operation to ban poison gas.
   On trade issues, the officials said Bush told the Soviet leader
the United States would support granting Moscow observer status in
the General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, a 97-nation trade
organization, once the Kremlin eases emigration restrictions, as it
has promised.
   Bush also proposed negotiations begin on a trade agreement that
would also lift tariff and import controls against Soviet goods
entering the United States, the official said.
   The trade restrictions were imposed by Congress in the mid-1970s
with the aim of forcing the exodus of Soviet Jews. The official
made clear that Bush's offers were conditional, based on completion
of Soviet legislation to establish freedom of travel. Completion of
that landmark law is expected within a month.
   One of the restrictive U.S. laws, known as the Jackson-Vanik
Amendment, has for many years denied the Soviet Union the kind of
access to U.S. markets enjoyed by most other nations by imposing
high tariffs. The other legislation, known as the Stevenson
Amendment, denies export credits to Moscow.
   Apart from imminent action on emigration, the Soviet Union is in
the midst of reconstructing its economy under Gorbachev's
perestroika campaign.
   A U.S. official said that Bush urged Gorbachev to move toward a
market-pricing system. But he gave no indication how Gorbachev
responded to any of the President's propositions. But Gorbachev is
known to want Soviet entry to the General Agreement on Tariffs and
Trade (GATT).
   Bush proposed only observer status for the Soviets _ not full
membership. It would be granted next year, the official said.
   Bush's proposal for an international summit in Vienna follows
one by Gorbachev last week to have the leaders of the United
States, Canada and 33 European countries meet next year to ease
East-West divisions.
   The treaty that would be signed is under negotiation in the
Austrian capital between NATO and the Warsaw Pact. It would reduce
U.S. and Soviet troops in Europe to 275,000 each and also cut
tanks, artillery and other non-nuclear weapons from the Atlantic
Ocean to the Ural Mountains in the Soviet Union.
   The two key obstacles at this point concern what kinds of
airplanes to scale back and whether to include a Turkish port
through which supplies flow to Turkish troops on Cyprus.
   The strategic arms reduction treaty, known as START, is under
negotiation in Geneva between the United States and the Soviet
Union.
   Bush said Baker and Shevardnadze should focus on such nagging
problems as how many nuclear-tipped air-launched cruise missiles to
be permitted, whether missiles not deployed on bombers, submarines
or in silos should be scrapped and measures to prevent the
disguising of missile tests.
   In the area of human right, Bush told Gorbachev that ``all
outstanding human rights cases'' should be resolved before that
meeting, an official said.
   He presented a list of cases to the Soviet leader. The number
was not disclosed.
</TEXT>
