<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--LampsAuctioned     12-02 0168</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Lamps Auctioned,0172</SECOND>
<HEAD>Record for 20th Century Decorative Art</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A glass and bronze lotus lamp sold at Sotheby's
Saturday for $1.76 million, a record price for a 20th century
decorative work of art, the auction house said.
   The lamp by the French artists Daum Nancy and Louis Majorelle
had been expected to bring $500,000 to $600,000, said Sotheby's
spokeswoman Laura Stewart.
   Each of its three sockets supports a mold-blown, wheel-carved
glass shade in pink and green, with the largest in the shape of a
lotus blossom and the other two molded as lotus buds. It was made
about 1900.
   A lamp by Emile Galle sold for $1.1 million, a record for the
French artist, Stewart said. The price was within the pre-sale
estimate.
   The 1902 lamp, known as ``Les Coprins'' (The Mushrooms), is made
of internally decorated and intaglio-carved glass and wrought iron.
   The buyers and sellers asked not to be identified, Stewart said.
The prices include the auction house's 10 percent commission.
</TEXT>
