<FIRST>r a AM-Obit-Welch     12-02 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Obit-Welch,0178</SECOND>
<HEAD>Richard Welch, Former Boeing Commercial Airplane Co. President, Dead
at 69</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Richard W. Welch, who rose from accounting clerk
to president of Boeing Co.'s commercial aircraft division, has died
at age 69.
   Welch died Tuesday in a hospital of a neurological disease.
   A native of Baraboo, Wis., Welch moved to Bellevue, Wash., with
his family. He served in the Army field artillery during World War
II, then earned a degree in economics from the University of
Washington.
   He was hired by Boeing as an accounting clerk in 1949. He was
promoted to chief of material and property accounting in 1954 and
vice president for finance and contracts in 1968.
   He was later named executive vice president of Boeing's largest
division, now known as Boeing Commercial Airplanes, and served as
president from 1981 until his retirement in 1985. During his last
year he also served as a senior vice president of Boeing Co.
   Survivors include his wife, Nancy; a sister; three sons and a
daughter; and five grandchildren.
</TEXT>
