<FIRST>d a AM-BRF--Pepper'sSpecs     12-02 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Pepper's Specs,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fisherman Finds Spectacles from Pepper Statue</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fisherman found the 5-pound bronze spectacles
snatched from a statue of the late U.S. Rep. Claude Pepper in a
downtown park.
   George Valdes, who was fishing near Jose Marti Park, found the
glasses broken in two and turned them in to police Friday.
   Valdes was fishing Thursday on the banks of the Miami River when
he saw two children about 7 years old playing with what looked like
pieces of copper.
   ``They were playing like swords with them and I scolded them:
`That's Senor Pepper's! Give them to me,''' said the 30-year-old
drummer.
   The specs will be screwed in rather than soldered on Pepper's
nose this time around, said sculptor Tony Lopez, who did the
statue. The result of a $60,000 fund-raising effort, the 9-foot
statue was unveiled in October and the glasses were swiped three
weeks later.
   Pepper, D-Fla., died in May at age 88.
</TEXT>
