<FIRST>u i AM-Summit-CentralAmerica     12-02 0254</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Summit-Central America,260</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bush Raises Issue of Soviet Arms in El Salvador</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSAXLOKK BAY, Malta (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush appealed to Soviet
leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev during their summit talks Saturday to
halt the flow of Soviet weapons to rebels in El Salvador, but U.S.
officials said the issue was not resolved.
   Gorbachev, according to the officials, said he did not know how
the arms get to the Central American country.
   The United States alleges that the weapons, including Soviet
anti-aircraft launchers, are channeled through the leftist
governments of Cuba and Nicaragua. A plane that crashed last
weekend in El Salvador carried a cache of Soviet weapons, the State
Department charged.
   U.S. officials at the summit, declining to be identified, called
the dispute the biggest stumbling block to a further improvement in
superpower relations.
   Secretary of State James A. Baker last week denounced the
weapons flow as a ``relic of the Cold War.''
   He had taken the issue up in September with Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A . Shevardnadze in Jackson Hole, Wyo. The Soviets
promised at that time to stop direct deliveries and to try to stem
the flow, U.S. officials said.
   The Salavadoran rebels are using the arms in their war against a
U.S.-backed, right-wing government.
   The Bush administration, meanwhile, refuses to stop providing
weapons to rebels fighting a Marxist government in Afghanistan. The
State Department has ruled out a tradeoff with Moscow halting
Soviet arms for Salvadoran rebels and U.S. arms to the Afghans.
</TEXT>
