<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 1812EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-MissingPlane     12-02 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Plane,0448</SECOND>
<HEAD>Delay Reported in Start of Search for Lost Commuter Plane</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WESTERLY, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The search for a commuter plane that
disappeared off Rhode Island last week was delayed at least 20
minutes until somebody at the Westerly airport noticed it was late,
a newspaper reported Saturday.
   Eight people were aboard when the plane presumably crashed into
Block Island Sound while flying the 17 miles from the island to
Westerly on Tuesday. The Coast Guard gave up searching for
survivors Wednesday night after finding debris and two dead dogs
from the plane.
   National Transportation Safety Board officials said
investigators had not recovered the plane, but were compiling
various evidence, including records showing the aircraft underwent
extensive repairs for a crack three years ago.
   Officials planned to use sonar Monday to scan the ocean floor
for debris. New England Airlines President William Bendokas told
The Providence Journal-Bulletin the search was delayed because
ticket agents at Westerly did not realize the flight had not
arrived until 7 p.m., when they called him at home and said it was
20 minutes overdue.
   The pilots commonly fuel and unload planes before checking in
with the terminal desk, he said. Bendokas said he called the
Federal Aviation Administration at 7:15 p.m., alhough Robert A.
Ferreira, manager of the FAA center at Quonset Point, said his logs
show the call coming in at 7:35 p.m.
   FAA records from the agency's Oklahoma City office indicate the
airplane underwent repairs for a crack on July 1, 1986. Seventeen
separate steps were taken to fix the hole, said FAA spokeswoman
Linda Whitfield.
   ``The company was doing more maintenance than required by the
manufacturer'' on the 1969 model Britten-Norman Islander, said NTSB
spokesman Alan Pollock in Washington.
   Pollock said an examination of a dog that was accompanying one
of the missing passengers indicated the animal drowned. He would
not speculate whether that meant the airplane broke up when it hit
the water.
   Seas were 5 to 6 feet and water temperatures about 45 degrees,
making survival unlikely for anyone in the water.
   The plane was not tracked on air traffic control radar and there
were no radio calls for help before the crash, NTSB spokesman Ted
Lopatkiewicz said.
   Since older commuter planes normally don't carry the ``black
box'' flight recorders that are on larger commercial airliners, the
NTSB said investigators were piecing together other evidence,
including the pilot's background.
   Pilot John Beck Jr., 46, had flown part-time for the airline for
about six months, Bendokas said. Beck previously flew for the Navy
and for about 10 years with area charter operations, he said.
</TEXT>
