<FIRST>u a AM-AMAMeeting 1stLd-Writethru a0644 12-02 0731</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AMA Meeting, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0644,0744</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigation Clouds Image as Medical Association Meets</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `Making the ...' with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
AMA trustees saying Sammons acted within his authority, proposing outside
auditor, CORRECT that Sammons is widely admired, sted was; picks up 8th
graf, `In 1987 ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAULINE JELINEK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As leaders of the American Medical Association
prepare to meet to set policy on U.S. health-care issues, some
members are questioning how well the group is running itself after
recent revelations about money-losing deals.
   The AMA is coping with a controversy involving an executive's
pension losses in a high-risk stock market fund and a loan to
another executive who defaulted.
   The disclosures have shaken the conservative image of the
Chicago-based AMA, which with 300,000 members is the nation's
largest organization for doctors.
   ``It's a huge embarrassment to us, to the profession and to the
organization,'' said one East Coast doctor and AMA member who spoke
on condition of anonymity. ``We are concerned about our image
because so much of medicine is based on trust.''
   A resolution calling for the AMA's top executive to step aside
during an investigation is expected to go this week to the group's
House of Delegates. The policy-setting body is meeting in Honolulu
Sunday through Wednesday to consider a host of other issues as
well, including patients' rights and funding for AIDS care.
   Last month, four AMA affiliates passed resolutions concerning
revelations that Executive Vice President Dr. James H. Sammons had
approved two money-losing deals for other top association
executives.
   Making the matter even more painful, doctors say, is that
Sammons is widely admired within the association as an eloquent and
effective spokesman and has been credited with saving the AMA from
financial disaster when he took the job in 1974.
   The AMA's Board of Trustees, after receiving a report from the
law firm doing the investigation, issued its own report Saturday
concluding Sammons had ``acted within the scope of his authority.''
   The report, which will go to delegates for ratification this
week, also said the board will restructure its committees and hire
a new outside auditing firm to try to provide the type of
accountability sought in the affiliates' resolutions. The trustees
declined to comment on the report.
   In 1987, Sammons approved a $353,000 reimbursement to Chief
Operating Officer Whalen M. Strobhar for losses he suffered in the
``Black Monday'' stock market crash. Sammons said he ordered the
reimbursement after Strohbar reported that his $1.4 million in
pension funds was moved by mistake from relatively safe
money-market funds to high-risk but potentially more lucrative
investments.
   Two years later, Sammons reversed his decision after AMA
attorneys said the transfer of funds before the Oct. 19, 1987,
market crash was not a mistake but a ``deliberate act.''
   When the deal was reported in a Chicago Sun-Times investigation
in October, Strobhar, 57, resigned and agreed to repay with
interest what he acknowledged was an ``inappropriate''
reimbursement.
   In the second deal, the AMA lost $50,000 on a $267,000 loan
Sammons approved in May 1985 to help another top executive buy a
luxury condominium while he was going through a divorce.
   AMA counsel Kirk Johnson said there was nothing unusual about
the loan to Richard A. Noffke, 42, then deputy executive vice
president in charge of real estate and other financial affairs.
   But Noffke defaulted on the loan, forcing the AMA to foreclose
and costing it $50,000. Several months after the loan, Noffke lost
his $187,500-a-year job in a management reorganization.
   The revelations about Strobhar's stock market loss prompted the
Illinois State Medical Association to call for the investigation of
AMA financial practices, as well as a review of the association's
administrative structure.
   The doctors' societies of Delaware and the District of Columbia
asked for a curtailment of the broad financial discretion of the
chief executive.
   The Washington State Medical Association said Sammons should be
put on administrative leave until the investigation is closed.
   Mark Meister, executive director of the Medical Society of
Delaware, said his group's resolution wasn't meant to express a
lack of confidence in the AMA or Sammons.
   He said the society is urging establishment of a system of
financial accountability and checks and balances so the chief
executive won't be solely responsible for non-budget disbursements
such as those made to Strobhar and Noffke.
</TEXT>
