<FILEID>AP-PX-12-02-89 2307AET</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-DesertQuake     12-02 0224</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Desert Quake,0228</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moderate Earthquake Shakes Southern California</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM SPRINGS, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A moderate earthquake under the San
Jacinto Mountains jolted an 85-mile stretch of Southern California
on Saturday, but there were no reports of damage or injury,
authorities said.
   The quake hit at 3:16 p.m. and had an estimated strength of 4.3
on the Richter scale, California Institute of Technology spokesman
Hall Daily said in Pasadena. The epicenter was 16 miles southwest
of Palm Springs.
   The National Earthquake Information Center in Golden, Colo.,
estimated the quake's magnited at 4.5 and put its center 15 miles
southwest of Palm Springs, said geophysicist John Minsch of the
U.S. Geological Survey.
   Magnitude estimates from various monitoring points often differ.
   No injuries or damage were reported, said a Palm Springs police
lieutenant who declined to give his name.
   The quake was also felt in Pomona, 70 miles west of Palm Springs
in northeastern Los Angeles County, and in Indio 15 miles east of
the desert resort.
   An earthquake of 3.5 on the Richter scale can cause slight
damage in the local area, 4 moderate damage, 5 considerable damage,
6 severe damage. A 7 reading is a ``major'' earthquake, capable of
widespread heavy damage; 8 is a ``great'' quake, capable of
tremendous damage. The killer earthquake in the San Francisco Bay
area was put at 7.1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
