<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     12-02 0364</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nine Episcopalians Accused of Helping Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Episcopalian minister and
eight members of his church detained two weeks ago were charged
with helping leftist rebels and transferred to prison, a human
rights group said Saturday.
   Americas Watch, the human rights group, said the nine
Salvadorans who had been in police custody since Nov. 19-20were
transferred to prison to await trial after charges were filed
against them Friday.
   The human rights group, which is based in New York, made the
statement from its office in El Salvador.
   There was sporadic shooting in San Salvador's northern Mejicanos
district early Saturday, but it ended by daylight and military
officials said the capital was quiet. The rebels launched a major
offensive three weeks ago, attacking numerous targets in San
Salvador.
   The military press office said 19 guerrillas and 10 soldiers
were killed in clashes Friday in Mejicanos and the eastern
Soyapango district. More than 1,000 people were reported killed
during the rebels' offensive.
   Business activity was generally normal in San Salvador on
Saturday, and crews were repairing eletrical lines destroyed by the
guerrillas.
   The Rev. Luis Serrano Lorente and eight members of his Episcopal
church, including its lawyer and social programs directors, were
arrested in police raids Nov. 19 and 20.
   They are accused of allowing rebels to hide trucks loaded with
homemade mortars at their church the night before an Oct. 30 attack
on the Defense Ministry.
   Mortar shells were fired from two trucks, killing a gas station
attendant working near the ministry compound and wounding 15 people.
   Sources at Serrano's church told The Associated Press that armed
guerrillas forced their way into the church compound on Oct. 29 and
spent the night there. They said none of the church members was a
participant in the mortar attack.
   The government has accused Salvadoran and foreign workers
involved in church and human-rights organizations of supporting the
rebels.
   President Alfredo Cristiani on Friday referred to the rebels'
Farabundo Marti National Liberation Front as a ``minority joined by
internationalists who come here to murder Salvadorans.''
   The 10-year-old civil war has claimed at least 71,000 lives.
</TEXT>
