<FIRST>r a AM-LynchAquitted 1stLd-Writethru a0615 12-02 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lynch Aquitted, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0615,0403</SECOND>
<HEAD>Husband Acquitted In Slaying of Couple, Kidnap of Infant Son</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with reax from Lynch, families
of victims; picks up 8th graf, `Prosecutors accused ...' ADDS byline.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By THERESA HUMPHREY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DOVER, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused of helping his wife kill a
couple in order to take their 9-day-old son was acquitted Saturday
on all counts in the Christmas Eve 1987 kidnap-slaying.
   Jurors returned the innocent verdicts after more than three days
of deliberations in the case of Richard Lynch.
   Lynch claimed his wife, Joyce, had duped him into thinking she
was pregnant, and that he was unaware the child he thought was
Richard Lynch III was not their child.
   ``Oh Daddy, it's over,'' the defendant said as he embraced his
father after court was adjourned.
   Joyce Lynch was found guilty in June of killing Joseph and
Beverly Gibson of Hazletteville, snatching their infant son,
Matthew, and trying to pass him off as her own. She was sentenced
to life in prison without possibility of parole.
   At her trial, Mrs. Lynch had argued unsuccessfully that her
husband controlled her by injecting her with overdoses of a strong
painkiller and that she thought the killings were all a dream.
   The victims' parents avoided reporters after Saturday's verdict.
But the Rev. Kenneth Valentine, a spokesman for the families, said
they were shocked by the decision, which he called ``a nightmare.''
   ``It's hard for us to fathom that one person could have done all
that they did _ murdered two people, kidnapped a baby, Christmas
Eve morning at 1:30 or so,'' he said.
   Asked outside the courthouse if he planned to divorce his wife,
Lynch said, ``More than likely.''
   Concerning the Gibsons, he said, ``I feel sorry for what
happened. Ain't nothing I can do to change it.''
   Prosecutors accused the couple of stalking Gibson, 32, and his
wife, 27, for at least a week before gunning then down at the
mobile home on Dec. 24, 1987, and then taking the infant. The
Gibsons' 5-year-old daughter and 1-year-old son were not hurt.
   When the Lynches were arrested Jan. 7, 1988, they still had
Matthew Gibson, whom they referred to as their son Richard Lynch
III. Police found them by tracing telephone calls from their
Houston, Del., home to the Gibsons' home.
</TEXT>
