<FIRST>r a AM-CraneCollapse     12-02 0603</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crane Collapse,0619</SECOND>
<HEAD>Investigator To Question Subcontractor in San Francisco Crane Collapse</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investigation of a San Francisco crane
collapse that killed five people will explore possible criminal
wrongdoing by a subcontractor for rehiring a crane operator after
he made nearly ``catastrophic'' mistakes, a newspaper reported
Saturday.
   In Oakland, meanwhile, it was reported that the subcontractor
had been cited for safety violations four times in the past four
months.
   Erection Co. executives will be questioned about the work and
medical history of operator Lonnie Boggess, who died in the
accident, Hamilton Fairburn, deputy chief of California's
Occupational Safety and Health Administration, told the Seattle
Post-Intelligencer.
   Any criminal involvement ``would depend on why they rehired him
and what evidence they had at that time to feel assured that he was
OK,'' Fairburn said.
   Newspapers have reported that Boggess said in a sworn statement
last summer in his divorce case that he was upset over a custody
dispute and made job mistakes that nearly caused ``catastrophic
injury to fellow employees.''
   Boggess had tried to commit suicide twice during the past nine
months and had been hospitalized for psychiatric observation twice
since March, according to court documents obtained by McClatchy
Newspapers.
   There also have been published reports that Boggess had a
history of alcohol problems, as well as suggestions that he may
have suffered a heart attack at the time of the accident.
   Boggess didn't report for work between April and October,
according to employees of his union.
   If the firm laid him off because of his mental state, it ``would
have to show how he was able to return to work,'' Fairburn said.
   The cab of the crane made a sudden 180-degree turn Tuesday while
the crane's height was being increased from 16 to 20 stories at the
construction site of a new high-rise.
   Fairburn said investigators are focusing on human error as the
likely cause of the crane collapse, which showered tons of steel on
the city's busy financial district.
   It takes deliberate action to release the ``dead man's switch,''
which locks the crane in place, Fairburn said. Investigators still
haven't ruled out a mechanical failure, though, he added.
   The cab, along with other parts of the crane, has been taken to
an undisclosed yard where it will be studied by experts.
   Fairburn said he is aware of published reports that Boggess had
a history of alcohol and drug abuse and has asked the coroner to
speed a toxicology report. Coroner's officials have said blood
alcohol test results will be available in about two weeks.
   Tom Hanley of the California OSHA office in Oakland said state
inspectors have cited Erection Co. four times and fined it $1,500
since Aug. 4 for work on a $122 million, 22-story building in that
city, The Tribune reported Saturday.
   The company was cited for not requiring a worker to wear a
safety belt, failing to provide adequate safety platforms for
workers, failing to post safety rules at the site and carrying out
hazardous crane operations by lifting more than one steel beam at a
time. The first citation came after an ironworker fell 35 feet and
was injured while welding at the site.
   Earlier this week, the Department of Labor and Industries in
Washington state, where Erection is based and Boggess lived, said
the subcontractor had been cited 20 times for safety violations in
the past three years, including once for a fatal accident and four
times for accidents involving injuries.
   Washington regulators have fined the company $117,610 since the
beginning of 1987 but Erection is appealing six cases representing
$99,770 of the fines.
</TEXT>
