<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--MountainCrash     12-02 0160</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Mountain Crash,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Killed in Small Plane Crash in New Mexico</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LINCOLN, N.M. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine plane crashed Saturday
afternoon while approaching a mountain airport in snow and fog,
killing both people aboard, officials said.
   ``Weather was a factor. It was snow showers and fog,'' said Dave
Wingert, area manager in charge of the Albuquerque Air Route
Traffic Control Center. ``They were conducting an instrument
approach to Sierra Blanca.''
   The names of the victims were not immediately disclosed.
   An instrument flight plan was filed for the Beechcraft King Air
90 before it left Carlsbad, Calif., for Sierra Blanca Airport,
Wingert said.
   The plane crashed in the Capitan Mountains of south-central New
Mexico three miles east of Lincoln and about 20 miles northeast of
the resort community of Ruidoso.
   Rescuers planned to remain on the scene overnight to guard the
plane until Federal Aviation Administration investigators could
arrive Sunday, said Yolanda Mills, a state police dispatcher in
Alamogordo.
</TEXT>
