<FIRST>r a AM-Accountant-Slaying     12-02 0515</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Accountant-Slaying,0529</SECOND>
<HEAD>Slay Victim's Husband Ordered to Submit Blood, Hair Samples</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HUNTINGTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An affluent accountant whose wife was
strangled last week was ordered to cooperate in the murder
investigation by giving fingernail scrapings, blood and hair
samples to authorities.
   The order Friday by Cabell County Circuit Judge Dan O'Hanlon
came several hours before a land company sued Lyle B. McGinnis Jr.,
42, charging he swindled the company out of more than $5.64 million
since 1980 and set a fire in his office to destroy the evidence.
   Nighbert Land Co. of Maryland, which handles coal leases in
Mingo County, alleged that McGinnis also took $649,000 from a
corporate stock account he established for Nighbert.
   Kathy McGinnis was found dead behind a St. Albans shopping
center Wednesday afternoon, 15 hours after apparently being
strangled at her home in Huntington. Police did not find Lyle
McGinnis until 36 hours later, when he was involved in a single-car
accident in eastern Kentucky.
   McGinnis did not return telephone calls left at his house or at
his parents' home Friday. Cabell County Sheriff Ottie Adkins said
McGinnis has refused to talk to officers on the advice of his
attorney.
   Police visited McGinnis in an Ashland, Ky., hospital after the
accident to question him about his wife's slaying, but allowed him
to be released when he wouldn't answer questions.
   ``His attorney was down there last night, but he didn't want to
make any comment,'' Adkins said Friday.
   The sheriff wouldn't say whether McGinnis was a suspect. State
police and sheriff's officials from West Virginia and Kentucky
pored over McGinnis' car Friday to look for evidence.
   Nighbert's attorney, Michael J. Farrell, said McGinnis purchased
an interest in the land company in 1979 or 1980 and was named its
accountant in early 1980. Beginning that same year, he allegedly
diverted money to himself, his business or a joint account with his
wife, Farrell said.
   In addition, the lawsuit said, McGinnis failed to pay Nighbert's
taxes since 1980, prompting federal officials to seize the
company's assets. Internal Revenue Service agents were to look over
the records Aug. 22, but the documents were lost in an Aug. 20 fire
at McGinnis' office.
   ``McGinnis caused a fire to be set for the purpose of destroying
Nighbert records,'' the lawsuit said.
   The lawsuit seeks the return of $5 million and punitive damages
of $10 million. It also seeks any additional money that might be
found and asks that McGinnis be forced to pay any federal or state
penalties.
   Nighbert fired McGinnis in October, Farrell said.
   Nighbert obtained an injunction prohibiting McGinnis from
disposing of any of his assets, which Farrell said included a jet
and several cars. Court records show McGinnis in June 1986 paid
$495,500 for an elaborate home just east of Huntington and held
other property in the county.
   In the August fire, McGinnis said robbers broke into his office,
tied him to a chair and set a fire. There were signs of a scuffle,
but police did not close the books on that case.
</TEXT>
