<FIRST>r a AM-Plano-Soviets     12-02 0313</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plano-Soviets,0323</SECOND>
<HEAD>City Council Changes Mind, Decides To Become Sister City With Soviets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Summit Rdp, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLANO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This Dallas suburb's city council changed
its mind and agreed to seek a sister city in the Soviet Union even
though many residents made it clear they consider the Cold War far
from over.
   Council members voted 5-2 to endorse a program that will provide
for student, cultural and business exchanges with a Soviet city to
be determined later, according to The Dallas Morning News.
   ``I think the city council should be proud of themselves,'' Bob
Weidman, president of the Plano Soviet Sister City Program Inc.,
said after Friday's vote. ``They came through and in my estimate
did what was right.''
   Nevertheless, most of the more than 40 people who spoke on the
issue before the council vote opposed the plan.
   Ray Williams said he still believes Communists are out to
dominate the world despite the recent liberalization sweeping
across Eastern Europe.
   ``This is part of the most massive propaganda campaign, which we
swallow hook, line and sinker,'' Williams said. ``If Plano becomes
part of this program, we are approving of the Communist government
by adding the city of Plano stamp of approval.''
   Councilman Mike Teague, who opposed the measure, said there has
been ``too much sacrifice and too much loss to just forgive and
forget.''
   ``I'm about as excited as anybody else about the Berlin Wall,
but what's been torn down can be built back up.''
   The council had rejected a similar proposal seven months ago.
Several members who changed their minds said they were influenced
by the National League of Cities meeting last week in Atlanta.
   The preservation of the human spirit was stressed at the
conference, ``and a new spirit needs to be generated,'' Councilman
Mike Meyer said. ``This is a good chance for us to do that.''
</TEXT>
