<FIRST>r i AM-Peru-Rebels     12-02 0232</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru-Rebels,0238</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leftist Rebels Drown Worker in Gasoline</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leftist guerrillas raided an irrigation
project, drowned a worker in a tank of gasoline and tried to
recruit others to join the insurgency, police reported Friday.
   They said 30 rebels armed with guns, dynamite and machetes
attacked a workers camp at Ichucruz, 25 miles south of Ayachuco in
the Andean highlands, Thursday night.
   The guerrillas of the Maoist Shining Path group dynamited
vehicles and machinery and ransacked the warehouse, authorities
said. When a watchman resisted they tied his hands behind his back
and threw him into a tank of gasoline, according to police.
   About 80 workers were at the camp of the Rio Cachi project.
Before leaving, the guerrillas urged the workers to join the revolt
and threatened those who remained with the project.
   Godofredo Cordoba, the engineer in charge of the project, said
it is designed to irrigate 37,000 acres of cropland, produce
electricity and provide drinking water.
   He said Thursday's attack was the fifth time Shining Path rebels
have raided the camp. In December 1988 they killed four engineers.
   Police said 200 people were detained in a search for suspects
and army units were dispatched to pursue the rebels.
   The Shining Path began its insurgency in 1980 near Ayacucho, 235
miles southeast of Lima. The government says more than 17,000
people have been killed in guerrilla-related violence.
</TEXT>
