<DOCNO> AP891202-0142 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0126EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Greece     12-02 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece,0520</SECOND>
<HEAD>Interim All-Party Government Wins Confidence Vote</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Saturday cq in lead</HEAD>
<HEAD>By NIKOS KONSTANDARAS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An interim, all-party government headed by
Premier Xenophon Zolotas won a vote of confidence in Parliament
Saturday and a mandate to stabilize the Greek economy.
   With all three major parties supporting his administration,
Zolotas, an 85-year-old economist, received 292 votes in the
300-member Parliament. Five deputies were absent, one voted against
and two abstained in the roll call.
   Marina Dizi, the lone Environmentalist Party deputy, voted
against the government. Two legislators from former Premier Andreas
Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement abstained.
   The conservative, socialist and communist parties, which control
297 seats, agreed last month to form a joint government until new
elections in April. National elections in June and November left no
clear winner.
   Zolotas told Parliament when debate began Wednesday that his
priority will be to tackle government deficits and reduce the
government borrowing rate.
   According to central bank figures, the government will spend
$1.9 billion more than it receives in taxes this year, up from
$1.22 billion in 1988 and $844 million in 1987.
   Zolotas, widely credited with Greece's economic recovery after
World War II, blamed ``oversights of the last 20 years'' for the
economic situation. He promised ``frugality with economic
development.''
   The three parties will have to agree on specific measures, such
as boosting public utility rates and a proposed one-time tax on
personal and company earnings.
   They put aside their differences on Nov.22 and asked Zolotas, an
independent, to head the government.
   Constantine Mitsotakis's conservative New Democracy Party won
the most votes in elections on June 18 and Nov.5, but fell short of
a governing majority.
   Papandreou urged immediate acceptance of Zolotas' measures,
telling Parliament: ``Fiscal developments are serious, but they can
be controlled if quick measures are taken and are successful, and
they will be successful if they are taken quickly.''
   Mitsotakis also called for immediate action. ``If measures are
not taken before the holidays it will be too late,'' he said. ``We
will have a cash flow shortage by the end of December of ... ($1.3
billion) which the Bank of Greece will not be able to make up.''
   Hariloas Florakis, head of the communist-led Coalition of the
Left and Progress, asked the government to protect the standard of
living and wages of the workers, ``so as to allow us to support the
government until the end of its term.''
   The Bank of Greece, the central bank, has said the real income
of salaried workers decreased by 10 percent in the last two years
because of an annual inflation rate now estimated at 15-16 percent.
   All three party leaders told Parliament an unprecedented spirit
of cooperation exists among their organizations.
   The conservatives and communists joined forces this year to
indict Papandreou, then premier, on corruption charges. He is to be
tried by a special court next year.
   Mitsotakis said, ``The cleanup can continue, without anyone
claiming that petty political interests are being served.''
</TEXT>
