<FIRST>r i AM-Grenada     12-02 0293</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Grenada,0304</SECOND>
<HEAD>Public Employees Strike To Get Promised Pay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. GEORGE'S, Grenada (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 7,000 public employees began
a strike Friday after Prime Minister Herbert Blaize said his
government could not keep its promise to deliver about $9.3 million
in back pay.
   The strike call came near the end of the business day. It was
expected to shut down virtually all government offices starting
Monday.
   At a meeting attended by about 1,000 workers, union leaders
criticized Blaize's announcement Thursday night that the government
could not pay the retroactive wage increases covering the last
three years.
   Blaize said the government could not pay the money on Friday as
promised because it had not received funds ``from expected external
sources.'' He did not elaborate but said the money would be paid
within three months.
   The government has had trouble collecting export, property and
other taxes, and revenue shortfalls have forced it to borrow
heavily from banks.
   In 1987, imports were nearly three times the value of exports,
and the trade deficit was about $55 million for this Caribbean
island of 100,000 people.
   Leaders of the Public Workers Union, the Grenada Union of
Teachers and the Technical and Allied Workers Union vowed to
continue the strike until the money is paid. They issued a
statement calling Blaize's action unethical and ``a manifestation
of gross contempt.''
   Participating in the strike are teachers and employees of post
offices, banks, ports, customs, the telephone system, hospitals and
utilities.
   Several private organizations, including the Chamber of
Commerce, released a joint statement expressing their ``grave
concern resulting from this development and its potential impact on
the economy and stability of the country.''
   Most of this island's 7,000 government workers are members of
the three unions that ordered the strike.
</TEXT>
