<FIRST>r a AM-PlaneCrash 1stLd-Writethru a0782 12-02 0349</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Plane Crash, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0782,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Military Plane Crashes With Five Aboard; No Survivors Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to UPDATE with report of wing dipping and
to CLARIFY plane's mission as radar equipment check, sted infrared; CORRECT
spelling of Siegler, sted Sigler, and UPDATE with ID of civilian, make
other minor editing changes. No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LEXINGTON PARK, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A twin-engine Army cargo plane with
four crew members and a civilian on board crashed into a river
Friday as it approached Patuxent Naval Air Station, Army officials
said. No survivors were found.
   The CASA-212 aircraft plunged into the Patuxent River about 9:20
a.m., said John Ooley, Army spokesman at Fort Belvoir in northern
Virginia.
   A Washington television station quoted an Army spokesman as
saying the pilot was on his landing approach when the right wing
dipped and the plane crashed nose-first into the water.
   The aircraft, which left Davison Army Airfield at Fort Belvoir a
few minutes after 9 a.m., was scheduled to have its on-board radar
detection equipment checked at Patuxent, said Pentagon spokeswoman
Paige Eversole. The procedure is a routine part of the Army's
certification process, she said.
   Ooley said the civilian on the plane worked for Lear Siegler
International Corp., a company based in Stamford, Conn. He was
identified as Ronnie Whitely Jr., 31, of Alamogordo, N.M., by his
father, Whitely Sr. The other four on board were from Fort Belvoir.
   Identities of the other victims were withheld until their
families could be notified, Ooley said.
   Navy divers believed they had spotted one body in the wreckage,
submerged in 45 feet of water, 50 feet offshore, said John Romer,
spokesman at the naval station in St. Mary's County in southern
Maryland.
   Rescue crews worked until dusk and a floating crane was to be
used to lift the wreckage from the water, Romer said.m., Ooley
said. The investigation of the crash will be handled by the
Aviation Safety Board in Alabama, Ooley said.
   The CASA-212 was built in Spain and can be used for troop
transport, maritime patrols, paratrooper operations or
anti-submarine actions, Romer said.
</TEXT>
