<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0044EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-TritiumSales     12-02 0323</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tritium Sales,310</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oak Ridge Sales Resume</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Energy Department said Friday it was
resuming commercial sale of a key component of nuclear warheads
after concluding that amounts listed as missing hadn't been stolen
after all.
   The material, tritium, has been sold for 25 years in small
amounts for research and for making glow-in-the-dark markings, as
for clock faces, exit signs and airport runway markings in remote
areas.
   It is also used to boost the power of nuclear warheads and the
power thermonuclear weapons.
   Twice this year, the Department suspended commercial shipments
from the Oak Ridge National Laboratory in Tennessee. The first time
followed complaints of customers that they had not received as much
as 40 percent of the material they were billed for; the second
time, in October, followed the loss of a substantial fraction from
a trial shipment designed to test handling procedures.
   The department's announcement late Friday of the resumption of
shipments said: ``Four investigations of the tritium shipping
discrepancies have found no evidence to support the possibility of
theft or diversion ... Among the causes of the discrepancies were
deficiencies in equipment, measurement methods, procedures, records
and management and technical oversight'' as well as the unique
properties of tritium.
   Department spokesman Phil Keif said he was unable to assign a
percentage of the 5 grams listed as missing from commercial
shipments to the reasons given, but ``We think it is explainable''
by those reasons.
   ``We don't think tritium was stolen,'' Keif said.
   Tritium is a radioactive form of hydrogen, notoriously difficult
to confine in piping and containers. Officials said in October they
believed undetected leaks could be one cause of the missing
material.
   The department said it had revised its measurement techniques
and saw no need to revise its handling regulations.
   The nation's tritium production and inventories are secret, but
there have been estimates that only about 4 grams is needed for a
plutonium-powered warhead.
</TEXT>
