<HEAD>Teen Charged in Mother's Death Competent to Stand Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL BUELOW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state legislator's son who is accused of
killing his mother with a hunting arrow is competent to stand
trial, the youth's attorney said Friday.
   The defendant, Chad Goetsch, 19, appeared in Dodge County
Circuit Court at a brief competency hearing on a charge of
first-degree intentional homicide in the Nov. 8 killing of Carolyn
Goetsch, 51.
   Rep. Robert Goetsch, the husband of the victim and adoptive
father of the defendant, sat in a corner of the last row in the
courtroom. He left without comment at the end of the preceedings.
   Judge Daniel Klossner said he had received competency reports
from doctors at the Mendota Health Institute who examined Chad
Goetsch the last week of November.
   ``It's the defense's position at this time that Mr. Goetsch is
competent,'' said Chad Goetsch's attorney, Willima Retert, in reply
to Klossner's question of whether he could stand trial.
   Klossner set a Dec. 5 date for a hearing on motions regarding
evidence in the case. Chad Goetsch has yet to enter a plea to the
charge, which carries a maximum sentence of life in prison.
   When he was taken into custody, Chad Goetsch told authorities he
shot his mother accidentally while playing with a hunting bow at
the Goetsch farm house, according to the complaint.
   But Robert Goetsch said Chad shot his wife, then pointed an
arrow at him.
   ``My son was going to kill me,'' the lawmaker said in the
complaint.
   Robert Goetsch said he and his son fought, passing through a
hall and several rooms.
   Chad Goetsch, a freshman at Marquette University, had not lived
at home recently, said Dodge County Sheriff Stephen Fitzgerald.
