<FIRST>r a AM-CraneCollapse 1stLd-Writethru a0732 12-02 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Crane Collapse, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0732,0574</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crane Crash Investigators Zero in on `Dead Man's' Switch</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling throughout to Fairburn, sted Fairbanks.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES O. CLIFFORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators want to know why the ``dead
man's switch'' failed on a crane, letting tons of steel pour down
on a busy street and killing five people, a state official said
Friday.
   ``The brakes on the crane are its dead man's switch,'' said
Hamilton Fairburn, deputy chief of the state Occupational Safety
and Health Administration. ``It takes energy to release brakes.''
   The crane's cab made a sudden 180 degree turn Tuesday as the
crane's height was being increased from 16 to 20 stories at the
construction site of a new high-rise.
   There have been published reports that the crane's operator, who
was among those killed, had a history of alcohol problems and also
suggestions that he may have suffered a heart attack.
   The crane is being studied by experts, but Fairburn said going
over the wreckage would not be a quick job.
   The crane, capable of lifting 177 tons, had to be perfectly
balanced during the repositioning operation, according to Gordon
Marks, a vice president with Swinerton &amp; Walberg Co., the general
contractor for the project.
   Despite the necessary balancing, both Fairburn and company
officials agreed that repositioning a crane is not considered
dangerous.
   ``No one in our firm has ever seen or heard of an incident where
a crane collapsed while being raised from one position to
another,'' said Ned Gates, the firm's chairman.
   ``Historically, it's a very safe operation,'' said Fairburn.
   Both government and company investigators are trying to find out
why the cab suddenly went out of control.
   ``The crane's dead-man arrangement isn't like it is on a
motorcycle,'' said the investigator. ``There, it's the throttle.
You let go, it shuts off. With brakes that are locked in place, you
have to take deliberate action.''
   He said investigators must find out ``whether it was released by
the operator or if there was some malfunction.''
   Right now, he said, the probe is focusing on human error.
   Fairburn said he is aware of published reports that crane
operator Lonnie Boggess had a history that included alcohol and
drug abuse.
   ``We have expanded our investigation to look into that and have
asked the coroner to speed the toxicology report. The alcohol
concerns me because of the psychological and physiological problems
associated with it,'' he said.
   Coroner's officials have said blood alcohol test results will be
available in about two weeks.
   There also has been speculation that Boggess may have suffered a
heart attack.
   Boggess' sister, Genoa Hefke, said she spoke with a worker who
was on the ground and in radio contact with Boggess before the
accident.
   She said the worker told her that the radio suddenly went silent
and that Boggess, 45, may have had a heart attack.
   ``All of a sudden he stopped answering, and then it started
rocking back and forth,'' she said.
   But, said Fairburn, a heart attack wouldn't account for the cab
suddenly going out of control.
   ``Even if he had a heart attack and slumped forward, it is
relatively safe because the brakes are locked up. They have guards
on them so you can't slump over them. Again, it would take
deliberate action to release them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
