<FIRST>r i AM-Colombia-Extradite     12-02 0513</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Colombia-Extradite,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>Committee Approves Measure for Public Vote on Extradition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STAN YARBRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional committee ignored
government appeals Friday and approved a bill to have voters decide
if suspected drug traffickers should be extradited to the United
States for prosecution.
   Telling the committee members not to make themselves
``accomplices of drug traffickers,'' Interior Minister Carlos Lemos
Simmonds said approval of the measure would increase drug-related
violence.
   He also suggested drug traffickers were responsible for the
crash of a Colombian jetliner Monday. All 107 passengers and crew
were killed.
   If adopted by Congress and signed by President Virgilio Barco,
the bill would provide for a referendum to determine if the
extradition of Colombian drug suspects should continue.
   The Barco administration has sent nine suspected traffickers to
the United States since it reinstituted extradition on Aug. 18 as
part of an anti-drug fight following the assassination of a
presidential candidate. Drug traffickers were blamed for the
killing.
   Lemos Simmonds called the proposed bill ``monstrous'' and
``shameful.'' He said a referendum would lead to a national
bloodbath as drug traffickers would step up violence to intimidate
citizens into rejecting extradition.
   ``You are inviting Colombians not to a referendum but to the
slaughterhouse, because (the election) will provoke tremendous
violence, deaths and intimidation,'' he said.
   He also said he feared more drug-linked violence before the
presidential elections in May 1990.
   ``Don't dirty Colombia,'' the minister told the 35-member
committee. ``Don't become the accomplices of drug traffickers.''
   The committee voted 24-11 in favor of attaching the referendum
bill to legislation to amend the constitution. The House of
Representatives is scheduled to vote on the legislation Monday.
   The Senate then will have to ratify the referendum. Lemos
Simmonds said he would ask Barco not to sign the measure.
   Some members of the committee objected to the minister's
suggestion they were pandering to drug traffickers. Several said
the public had a right to decide if extradition should continue
amid a wave of terrorist violence.
   Authorities have blamed drug traffickers for some 200 bombings
that have killed 29 people and injured 238 across Colombia in less
than four months.
   Lemos Simmonds, citing examples of violence by drug traffickers,
spoke of ``planes that don't finish their journeys because they are
blown up.''
   Drug smugglers ``bring down aircraft,'' he added.
   He was referring to the Avianca Airlines Boeing 727 that
exploded minutes after taking off from Bogota's international
airport Monday on its way to the southern city of Cali.
   Lemos Simmonds told Caracol radio later that he based his
statements on claims of responsibility for the jetliner crash by
the Extraditables, a terrorist group linked to the Medellin cocaine
cartel.
   A man saying he represented the group told Caracol it blew up
the plane in retaliation for a police raid on the hideout of Pablo
Escobar, a leader of the Medellin cartel, on Nov. 22.
   Caracol later said it doubted the call's authenticity.
   Government investigators said they have not determined the cause
of the crash but it could have been from an explosive device.
</TEXT>
