<HEAD>Mississippi Sues Minister Who Runs Children's Home</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LUCEDALE, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A minister whose controversial children's
home spurred a law governing such operations is being sued by the
state for not complying with the statute.
   The Rev. Herman Fountain and his Bethel Children's Home are
named in the lawsuit as failing to register the church-operated
boarding home with the state.
   Fountain has contended he answers only to God and doesn't have
to abide by state law. The minister is free on $40,000 bond pending
appeal of a year's prison sentence stemming from a raid in 1988
that led to 72 children being taken into custody following
allegations of abuse at the home.
   The incident spurred the Legislature this year to pass a law
regulating all 24-hour child-care services, including those with a
religious affiliation.
   Fountain, a 40-year-old independent Baptist minister, was found
guilty of assault on a police officer, but was never charged with
any mistreatment or abuse of the children.
   Reached by telephone, the minister declined to comment on the
lawsuit.
   Fountain is accused of failing to turn over information to the
state concerning his boarding home for primarily wayward youths,
located on a 28-acre complex on the outskirts of Lucedale.
   The complaint also alleges that Fountain refused an inspection
by the State Fire Marshal's Office.
