<FIRST>r i AM-Nicaragua-Soviet     12-02 0236</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nicaragua-Soviet,0245</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviets Deny Telling Cuba, Nicaragua To Stop Arming Salvadorans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet official on Friday denied
that the Soviet ambassador here ordered the Nicaraguan and Cuban
governments at a secret meeting in Managua to stop shipping weapons
to leftist rebels in El Salvador.
   The French newspaper Le Monde on Wednesday quoted an
unidentified leader of Nicaragua's leftist Sandinista government as
its source.
   According to Le Monde, the man said Soviet Ambassador Valeri
Nikolaenko gave the order after Salvadoran authorities reported
finding two light planes bound from Nicaragua with arms for
Salvadoran rebels.
   ``We have spoken with our ambassador ... and he utterly denies
having made statements in this sense,'' said Igor Rybalkin, of the
international department of the Soviet Communist Party's
policy-making Central Committee.
   ``Besides, because of the very principle of our relations with
countries like Cuba, like Nicaragua, this is excluded.''
   President Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua has not denied the
Salvadoran accusation.
   Rybalkin said his government was concerned about the situation
in Central America, and the region's conflicts will probably be
discussed at the weekend summit between presidents Bush and Mikhail
S. Gorbachev.
   He said that althouth the agenda was open for the Gorbachev-Bush
summit, ``it's very possible, and I'm even sure, that the Central
American conflict is going to figure'' in their discussions.
   Rybalkin is on a goodwill tour of the region.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
