<FIRST>r a AM-PreschoolMolest     12-02 0339</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Preschool Molest,0349</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jurors May Have Reached Decision on Five More Counts, Judge Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jurors who turned in one verdict in the
McMartin preschool molestation case may be withholding five others
for fear of disrupting work on dozens of remaining counts, the
judge said Friday.
   The panelists may be trying to avoid explaining their verdicts
to friends and work colleagues while on a scheduled two-week
vacation that begins Dec. 16, Superior Court Judge William Pounders
said.
   On Tuesday, jurors handed in one sealed verdict, but they may
have reached a decision on five more of the 65 counts against
Raymond Buckey and his mother, Peggy McMartin Buckey, Pounders said.
   Buckey, 31, and his mother, 63, are charged with molestation and
conspiracy in connection with the alleged sexual molestation of 11
students at their now-defunct, family-owned school in Manhattan
Beach.
   The 2{-year-old proceeding, the nation's longest criminal trial,
has cost Los Angeles County more than $15 million.
   Meanwhile, the judge said he may not read the sealed verdict by
Dec. 15 as he had previously considered.
   The judge said he is considering sequestering the jury and
waiting until all the verdicts are in before reading them. Earlier,
he had indicated he had tentative plans to read the verdicts
piecemeal.
   Pounders previously had ordered the jurors to return verdicts as
they were reached, calling it ``an insane process'' but a way of
avoiding a potential mistrial if one of the 12 panelists is unable
to continue.
   No alternates are available, and the sealed verdicts become
legal only when the jurors affirm their decisions in court.
   ``The worst possible situation is to have verdicts that are not
legally effective and then lose jurors,'' Pounders said Friday.
   However, the judge said last month he could find no case law to
support his plan to accept sealed verdicts one at a time, and
Buckey's lawyer, Danny Davis, had objected to the procedure.
   Attorneys were to meet with the judge on Monday to discuss when
the verdicts should be read.
</TEXT>
