<SECOND>AM-Fishermen Lost,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>Search Called Off for Missing Lobster Boat</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. Coast Guard on Friday ended the search
for a lobster boat and its five-member crew after 11 days of rescue
efforts spanning thousands of miles of the Atlantic.
   ``It's a very difficult conclusion to reach, but we've come to
the point where our chances of success are about nil,'' Rear
Admiral Richard Rybacki said in a statement.
   Rybacki commands the First Coast Guard District in Boston, the
search operation headquarters where the search was launched after
the 72-foot Heidi Marie of Stonington, Conn., was reported missing
last week.
   Aircraft were dispatched more than 50 times in a hunt that
covered more than 100,000 square miles, Rybacki said.
   High winds and rolling seas on Friday hampered efforts to get
another glimpse of a submerged object rescuers thought might have
been a life raft.
   Missing are Mark Middleton, 33, of Norwich, Conn., the Heidi
Marie's captain; Michael Hare, 22, of Pawcatuck, Conn., Kenneth
Raymond Gould, 20, and Ray Morris III, 19, both of Westerly, R.I.,
and Arthur Banks, 25, of Ashaway, R.I.
   During the 11-day search, five flares were sighted, as well as
the Heidi Marie's emergency radio beacon and other debris. Efforts
to find the flares' origin failed.
</TEXT>
