<SECOND>PM-Digest Briefs,0579</SECOND>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EAST BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Top Communist Party leaders took bribes,
lived opulent lifestyles, went on luxurious vacations and managed
to squirrel away more than $50 billion in Swiss bank accounts, a
government investigator says.
   Shaking their heads in disbelief and disgust, members of East
Germany's Parliament listened to a litany of corruption involving
leaders who rigidly maintained a spartan society for their people
while indulging in excess.
   At a tumultuous session that ran late into Friday night,
Communist Party chief Egon Krenz declared his party's guilt but
sought to separate his new leadership from the aging and disgraced
figures now ousted from power.
   The 52-year-old Krenz boldly took responsibility for the party's
alleged misuse of power in 40 years of uncontested rule.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alvin Ailey, the dancer and choreographer of
jazz- and gospel-inspired works both accessible and exhilarating,
was hailed as a ``giant'' of modern dance after his death at age 58.
   Ailey's unique, dynamic style introduced black American music
and traditions into modern dance and helped transform it into a
popular art form. He died Friday after suffering for more than a
year from dyscrasia, a blood disorder.
   Singer Harry Belafonte, who toured with Ailey in 1958 and was
his longtime friend, said Ailey ``was just at the beginning of his
achievements. ... He was just at the threshold of his most
important creative years.''
   Ailey died at 4:55 p.m. at Lenox Hill Hospital, said Meg
Gordean, a spokeswoman for his company. Blood dyscrasia is a rare
disorder that affects the bone marrow and red blood cells, said
Ailey's physician, Dr. Albert Knapp.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government dropped its sedition
and racketeering case against three leading militants of the 1970s
after three years and more than $2 million in trial costs.
   U.S. Attorney Wayne Budd said Friday he will not retry the case.
Prosecutors claimed the radicals conspired to overthrow the
government by force through a series of bombings and bank robberies.
   ``Given the amount of effort already expended in the
investigation and prosecution, and the effort that would be needed
for a new trial, I have decided that the best course is not to seek
a retrial,'' he said.
   The federal jury cleared the three of sedition charges with a
partial verdict Monday, then deadlocked on whether alleged bombing
exploits constituted racketeering. A mistrial on the racketeering
charges was declared Wednesday.
