<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0028EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-U-Haul-Ryder     12-02 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-U-Haul-Ryder,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Denies U-Haul Motion in Suit Against Ryder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By INGER SANDAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PHOENIX (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge on Friday denied Phoenix-based U-Haul
International Inc.'s request to order 2,500 of a competitor's
biggest trucks off the road.
   U-Haul had asked Judge Paul G. Rosenblatt of U.S. District Court
for a preliminary injunction against Ryder System Inc., claiming
that Miami-based Ryder had equipped a fleet of 24-foot rental
trucks with a loading device similar to one U-Haul patented Jan.
30, 1973. The patent expires Jan. 30, 1990.
   The patented device, U-Haul maintained, gives its trucks a
competitive advantage of having lower rear decks, making them
easier for consumers to load and unload.
   Ryder told the judge it would suffer an $8 million loss in the
fourth quarter if it had to remove its trucks from the marketplace.
The trucks were introduced in early 1989.
   Both sides claimed victory Friday.
   ``It was very favorable to the U-Haul patent,'' said Thomas G.
Watkins III, an attorney for U-Haul.
   Watkins said Rosenblatt refused to issue the injunction largely
because the ``damage to Ryder, by having all 2,500 of its
infringing trucks parked, outweighed U-Haul's need for such a short
injunction.''
   ``We are gratified that the court has so far supported Ryder's
position,'' David R. Parker, president of Ryder Truck Rental, said
in a statement.
   Ryder contends it did not infringe on U-Haul's patent.
   The 2,500 trucks, which each cost about $30,000, represent about
8 percent of Ryder's fleet of consumer rental vehicles, Ryder said.
   U-Haul on Aug. 23 filed a patent-infringement suit against
Ryder, and on Sept. 15 filed for the preliminary injunction asking
that the trucks be taken off the road. A trial has yet to be
scheduled in the case, but is expected to go before Rosenblatt
during the first half of 1990.
</TEXT>
