<DOCNO> AP891202-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-12-02-89 0648EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-SIA     12-02 0752</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-SIA,0780</SECOND>
<HEAD>Securities Industry Group Proposals Ending Barrier With Banks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOCA RATON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wall Street leaders have declared an end
to their lengthy battle to keep banks out of the stocks and bonds
business, proposing to repeal the law that has governed the
nation's basic banking structure since the Depression.
   Directors of the Securities Industry Association, at the trade
group's annual convention here, on Friday endorsed a proposal for
new legislation to let subsidiaries of banks ``engage in a broad
range of securities and securities-related activities.''
   At the same time, the SIA said its plan would let brokers engage
in consumer banking businesses and join banks in having access to
the Federal Reserve's banking system, including the right to borrow
from the Fed in emergencies.
   The move appears to herald one of the biggest breaks yet in the
gradually crumbling wall separating banking and brokerage
activities, erected by the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933 amid the
financial crisis that followed the stock market crash four years
earlier.
   The barrier has been weakened chink by chink in recent years,
with the move toward financial deregulation and court decisions
permitting banks to make increasing inroads into what had formerly
been the brokers' turf.
   For example, many banks now participate in new offerings of some
kinds of securities, offer discount stock brokerage and sell shares
in mutual funds.
   Brokers, for their part, have also successfully launched forays
into businesses once considered the domain of the banks.
   In 1977, for example, they began to offer ``central assets
accounts'' that are technically not bank deposits, but come with
such features as check-writing, credit cards and lines of credit.
   The banking industry itself has used such brokerage services as
an argument for dismantling Glass-Steagall and allowing them
greater authority to enter the securities, insurance and real
estate businesses.
   Nevertheless, brokers have until now consistently sought to hold
the Glass-Steagall line, arguing that banks would enjoy several
unfair advantages in any arena of unfettered competition.
   They also say banks, with their federal deposit insurance and
links to the Federal Reserve System, should not be allowed to
expose themselves to risky ventures involving such things as the
sale of stocks.
   SIA officials said that banking groups played no part in
formulating their plan, which was made after a lengthy board
meeting late Friday.
   Hardwick Simmons, of Shearson Lehman Hutton, the outgoing
chairman of the SIA, said the Securities and Exchange Commission,
which regulates Wall Street, had been consulted and indicated that
it ``applauded the initiative.''
   The SIA said it would be holding talks with the next few weeks
with the Bush Administration, Congress and regulators to work out
details of what could amount to one of the most sweeping changes in
basic financial legislation in 56 years.
   One widely discussed possible result of any Glass-Steagall
reform has been mergers between the biggest banks and brokerage
firms.
   SIA did not address such specifics. However, most observers
point out that after any merger banking and brokerage activities
still would have to be conducted by separate subsidiaries of the
same company because brokers are regulated by the SEC while banking
is regulated by a different set of agencies, including the Fed,
Comptroller of the Currency and Federal Deposit Insurance Corp.
   ``We think that anything that leads to vastly increased
financial concentration is not in the broader interests of our
financial system,'' said Ken Guenther, spokesman for the
Independent Bankers Association of America, which represents
thousands of community banks.
   Asked about the late-afternoon development, Citicorp spokesman
John Maloney in New York said executives at the nation's largest
banking company would want to study the full resolution. But he
added, ``It's been a bad month for walls.''
   Outside observers see a variety of possible motives for the
SIA's change of strategy.
   Some believe that influential members of the securities business
felt it was useless and costly to keep fighting pitched battles, a
good many of which were being lost.
   Also, the proposal comes at a time when brokers are confronted
with a barrage of other problems, including high overhead and
shrinking profits from many of their traditional activities.
   When one prominent Wall Street figure, Chairman John Gutfreund
of the investment banking firm Salomon Brothers Inc., spoke to the
convention on Thursday, he declared:
   ``It is time for all the institutions in the financial services
industry to find some common ground.''
   A major mission facing U.S. financial institutions, he said, is
to ``work to design the post-Glass-Steagall world.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
